Ű·iäz{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "8a4dd0fa-98c5-45b6-b87a-521dfddc66ec", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.257848", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "c78c431c69b8d4180de4d9c40ae6c2b79b28ce78f70730aa63a47c742f47db6f"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "planktonrules", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-10-24", "title": null, "content": "\"The Secret Agent\" is a film I just saw at the Philadelphia Film Festival. Before I talk about the plot, I must warn you....this is NOT a film for kids or for those turned off by violence. The film features some brutal murders near the end and the story is certainly depressing...as it should be.\n\nThe story is set in Brazil in the 1970s. The nation had been under a military dictatorship since 1964 and the police in the film are uniformly shown to be evil. One of the people the police are looking for a man who you learn has done NOTHING illegal...he just got on the wrong side of a well-connected and evil man. So, much of the film consists of him hiding as well as various evil scum looking to kill him.\n\nIs this a recipe for a fun film? Certainly not! But it is very well made and teaches us about a period in history we might not know much about and should! Well made and a sad film that might leave you feeling a bit drained by the time it's completed."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "998a650f-360b-4d9c-a198-3bb7337642b8", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.257848", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "a5e68ac1cd58d393c60514634c7832da9abce53c8ce71ff35110d3f7a67a0879"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "evanston_dad", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-12-22", "title": null, "content": "I saw the movie \"Missing\" for the first time not that long ago. It was nominated for a Best Picture Oscar back in 1982 and is about a military coup in Chile and the search for a missing American that gets tangled up in the corruption of the Chilean and American governments and authorities.\n\n\"The Secret Agent\" tells a very different story from \"Missing,\" but because I had seen that movie recently I was thinking of it while watching this one. \"The Secret Agent\" is also set in a South American country, Brazil in this story, and it's also about how an innocent person gets trapped in the country because of the rampant corruption and the lack of reliable governance. Wagner Moura plays a man in witness protection trying to flee with his son, but in 1977 Brazil, witness protection was a grass roots operation not given any federal support, so it's basically a cat and mouse game to try to get out of the country before hired goons find him and kill him. All sorts of people are willing to be paid off, cops included.\n\nI'm not really sure who the secret agent of the title is supposed to be, unless it's an all-encompassing term meant to apply to any number of characters who are involved in their own private missions, most of them nefarious. The movie is being categorized as a thriller, and there are very suspenseful moments, but I'm not sure that's what it is first and foremost. It's more a slow-burn drama about people adrift in a system that seems intent on destroying them.\n\nMoura is quite good in the lead role, playing both the main character and then the grown up version of the main character's son in a final segment.\n\nGrade: A."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "b833cd7a-f80f-4b2b-afb9-0f16f52f70ed", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.257848", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "219b99fcc2b67e0ac0ca68415d48ef01d29f85af5a73344fff394ca93f26c257"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "LouD-91", "rating": 7, "date": "2025-11-02", "title": null, "content": "Kleber Mendon\u00e7a Filho's Secret Agent is a film of striking visual elegance. Its art direction is nothing short of superb, reconstructing 1970s Recife with a sense of texture and atmosphere that is both raw and poetic. The city emerges not just as a backdrop, but as a living, breathing character - a mix of beauty, decay, and tropical melancholy. The film is also populated by a gallery of eccentric characters, embodied by an equally eccentric cast that gives the work a peculiar and often intriguing rhythm.\n\nYet, despite this sensory richness, Secret Agent ultimately feels weighed down by its own self-awareness. The screenplay is disappointingly unoriginal and excessively self-referential, operating more as a parnassian memorial to the director's own childhood than as a gripping piece of suspense. What could have been an inventive political thriller dissolves into a predictable collage of Brazilian clich\u00e9s - corruption, nostalgia, and class tension - presented with a kind of weary inevitability that borders on pamphleteering.\n\nWagner Moura, despite critical praise, delivers an oddly muted performance. His restrained acting feels more absent than subtle, and the decision to have him play both father and son proves to be an unnecessary and somewhat embarrassing gimmick that adds little to the story's emotional weight.\n\nIn the end, Secret Agent stands as a technically accomplished but dramatically hollow film - a beautifully framed echo chamber where form triumphs over substance, and personal memory overshadows genuine cinematic tension."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "ced587a2-78f2-4860-8ce4-50ee26d056f8", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.257848", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "b0aeedbf369a9d90d1374822f456fb18fa06bb47efe9c497f602c86c80818d84"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "Rafa_halfeld", "rating": 10, "date": "2025-07-09", "title": null, "content": "Watched on Sydney Film Festival 2025\n\nWatching Kleber Mendon\u00e7a Filho's \"The Secret Agent\" feels less like observing a story unfold, and more like stepping into the humid, throbbing heart of Recife during Brazil's 1977 military rule. Forget the usual spy thriller beats; this is something far stranger, richer, and ultimately more haunting. It wraps you in the feverish embrace of Carnaval, not as spectacle, but as a desperate refuge for Marcelo (a profoundly compelling Wagner Moura), a researcher on the run seeking camouflage in the very city that birthed him.\n\nWhat lingers isn't just the plot, but the film's insistent, almost physical question: what survives when history tries to erase itself? Mendon\u00e7a Filho, a son of Recife pouring his own lifeblood into every frame, suggests memory itself is the battleground. He meticulously rebuilds a world - the textures of the time, the sidelong glances, the oppressive heat - not just for accuracy, but to etch onto the screen the stories official archives ignored. We feel the quiet terror faced by LGBTQ+ folk, witness the exploitation shadowing indigenous workers, see how the city itself becomes a living archive, a character pulsing with secrets and scars. Marcelo moves through it all with a fugitive's alertness, yet also with the weary, amused detachment of a tourist in his own collapsing world, adding a layer of profound melancholy.\n\nThe film possesses an extraordinary, unhurried confidence. It breathes. It pauses for moments of bizarre humour, startling eroticism, or pure, aching sadness. Mendon\u00e7a Filho is a sensualist, weaving a tapestry of sound - distant drums, whispered conversations, the city's own rhythm - and texture. He isn't afraid of the surreal: a severed leg appears, sexuality is presented with startling frankness, and meanings shimmer just below the surface like heat haze, resisting easy capture. That deliberate pace, stretching towards two hours and forty minutes, isn't indulgence; it's the very fabric of the experience. It demands your presence, inviting you not just to watch, but to inhabit Recife's streets and Marcelo's precarious existence.\n\n\"The Secret Agent\" isn't merely watched; it's absorbed through the skin. It's a challenging, deeply rewarding journey into the weight of the past and the fragile resilience of memory. This is filmmaking of rare courage, unafraid to linger in the uncomfortable spaces, to make us feel the ghosts whispering in Recife's humid air. It's a testament to the power of cinema to hold history close, ensuring some truths, at least, refuse to be forgotten."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "305e17af-4d98-4337-a28a-340d8820c9b5", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.258375", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "295b978419d982d42a2f935f6b911a5ecd42ecbcfe87ad4ca390142f9d7accbd"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "hrssagas", "rating": 9, "date": "2025-11-06", "title": null, "content": "The film has a Brazilian setting, not the stylized Brazilian setting, but one that makes you feel you actually know those people. In truth, the entire film gives this feeling.\n\nIt is a work that seems to be something you recognize. The way people speak, the \"villains\", everything is so symmetrically believable that the tension establishes itself naturally. The story does not deal with big points, it is the story of one person. Perhaps of many.\n\nIn this sense, the work is characterized by the characters, and all are very well realized and acted. Even though in certain moments scenes are prolonged in order to show these characters, as occurs throughout the film. Although time passes quickly while watching the film, it has many scenes that seem to serve only to extend the length of the work.\n\nEven with its excesses, one of the greats of Brazilian cinema."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "9fc6a105-069f-4568-abbd-6435d13586aa", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.258375", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "2f855664db9a9860f59bac9ab4d6a6f8d722cf638e82cc3a66fc912ca90d8480"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "sdlima-09135", "rating": 10, "date": "2025-11-07", "title": null, "content": "This movie is a conversation of Pernambuco with Pernambuco. Brazil with Brazil. Maybe may look strange for people Who are not from here (even silly) But every story (even the hairy leg one) is conected with Pernambuco's culture.\n\nExcelent direction, screenplay and acting by Wagner Moura.\n\nAbout the ending, spoilers ahead:\n\nA lot of people can find that it has a lot of loose endings, but that's the point. The whole movie is about resistance of memory and how unfortunaly, in Brazil, we tend to cast aside. The opening scene shows the indiference we have with violence and how we don't care with individuals. The ending doesn't explain what happened, Who did it, because in real life there's a million storys we just forget and treat like numbers (91 deads and Carnaval)\n\nFor people Who maybe feel this film is too long, this movie is not trying to entertain you. Is trying to speak with you, talk to you."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "1411163b-3927-470d-bd9c-6f41c8737a3b", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.258375", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "39d14ab16062f0a50662cf80636c7106db97fe07295d5018d7de4141eca53a53"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "goddess21112", "rating": null, "date": "2025-11-20", "title": null, "content": "A beautifully haunting movie. A patchwork of local culture and compelling characters, full of vibrant colors and music. It brings so much joy and pain all at once! It skillfully does what movies exist to do - remind us of life and death, of our own culture and history!\n\nAt first, the ending confused me. I wanted to know more, I wanted to see what happened next! But little by little I understood it. We don't want to see what happened, not really. Society doesn't want to be reminded of it. In reality, these cases are forgotten pieces of our history. And this is why movies like this should exist.\n\n\"The nineteenth century dislike of realism is the rage of Caliban seeing his own face in a glass.\" - Oscar Wilde."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "a3f0499a-7ad6-46ff-b5da-1f99be70782f", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.258375", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "bddc2adafd4dfa6402b2eefaf08d8d82617082503ce6cfa2189fa9b81bcd1950"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "oNerdcall", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-11-10", "title": null, "content": "The Secret Agent is more than just one of the great films of the year. It reflects the maturity of Brazilian cinema and the strength of a generation of filmmakers who have changed the way the country is viewed on the international stage. After the success of Walter Salles's I'm Still Here, which reignited Brazil's presence at the Oscars, the arrival of Kleber Mendon\u00e7a Filho's new film is surrounded by expectations, comparisons, and challenges. And perhaps that is precisely why The Secret Agent is not a film that will please everyone - nor does it try to be.\n\nSome may be frustrated by the slow pace, the prolonged silences, or the open ending. But it is precisely in these details that the beauty of The Secret Agent lies. Mendon\u00e7a does not want to shock, he does not want to give everything away on a silver platter. He wants to provoke reflection, he wants the viewer to leave the theater still processing what they saw - and what they felt. The discomfort the film causes is not a flaw; it is language.\n\nWhat we see here is mature Brazilian cinema, bold and aware of its importance. A film that looks to the past without becoming hostage to nostalgia, and that speaks about the present without needing to shout. O Agente Secreto is a deep dive into the history and soul of a country that is still trying to understand itself. It is a work that requires patience, but rewards it with intensity.\n\nIn the end, what Kleber Mendon\u00e7a Filho delivers is a film about memory, resistance, and belonging. A portrait of a man trying to escape himself, and of a country trying to forget what cannot be forgotten. With precise direction, an engaging script, and remarkable performances, O Agente Secreto is undoubtedly one of the great milestones of recent Brazilian cinema."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "7d3f3f71-cd8d-4a39-ad8e-93d4f37e6ab2", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.258375", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "171e96200d93749fb7207e6d49d01b8b71ec120785cc16f5d04a68169f7578ee"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "lizzcristina", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-11-08", "title": null, "content": "The Secret Agent is a film that, while ambitious, doesn't quite deliver on its promises. Its long runtime weighs heavily on the narrative, which oscillates between moments of great intensity and others where the pacing falters. The title, though intriguing, feels somewhat disconnected from the true essence of the story.\n\nThe acting is, without a doubt, the film's strongest asset. There's authenticity in the performances, well-crafted nuances, and a clear sense of commitment from the cast. The 1970s setting and the backdrop of Brazil's military dictatorship are excellent thematic choices, with immense potential to provoke reflection.\n\nHowever, the script loses focus. Too many storylines are introduced, too many subplots promised, only to be left unresolved or poorly developed. The result is a lingering sense of a film that aimed to say more than it could effectively organize.\n\nIn short, The Secret Agent is a visually competent and well-intentioned work that ultimately gets lost in its own ambition. The marketing built expectations of a powerful impact that the final product fails to sustain. In the end, it's a middling film, full of good ideas and solid performances, but with uneven execution."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "9fda667a-2fa1-4d07-953e-5aaf77d94d48", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.258375", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "5e3fe3b5e5f6c8159346ca2463a9795ededd391e8d5a02632218c7d811d42beb"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "fabiolpinheiro1993", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-11-16", "title": null, "content": "\"The Secret Agent\" is yet another proof of how great Brazilian cinema is. It's very comparable to I'm Still Here in terms of themes and filmmaking, but it's much more violent. The film tells an intense, heavy story set during a period of Brazilian history rich enough to spawn countless narratives. And despite its long runtime, it's always magnetic and gripping thanks to its incredible direction, cinematography, and-above everything else-the performances.\n\nThe cast, led by the legendary Wagner Moura (with a special shout-out to T\u00e2nia Maria), deliver Oscar-worthy, unforgettable work. There are even a few funny or lighthearted scenes sprinkled in to lift the mood, which I really appreciated.\n\nOn the other hand, the third act felt a bit underwhelming. The choice to use the same actor to play a different character (something I usually hate) felt unnecessary, and several loose ends were left hanging. You can fill them in with your own imagination, but with such a long runtime, those threads and the entire story deserved to be completed on screen. I would have trimmed some of the excess earlier to allow the story to conclude fully.\n\nThese issues prevent me from giving the film a higher rating-but it remains a great piece of art and filmmaking nonetheless."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "67298c3e-32db-465b-b833-34737c621398", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.258375", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "d2493e7a188ad8a38c9370193dd36d61498441be17e5e42bdff65a0c75c89c7c"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "lrobiner-801-44468", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-12-19", "title": null, "content": "... which spoiled the wonderfully colorful characters, beautiful cinematography and expert directing. I was never bored, even though nothing much happened during the majority of the movie. When something did happen, I was never sure why.\n\nThis felt like it was trying to be No Country For Old Men, but feel far short."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "57331e5c-1020-4de3-bd63-9d1c5ba42d5d", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.258375", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "12b8d52353c3bf645bff88ce1d48bf8429e12ddce0fe3544bb17d869b1c397f1"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "wel2005", "rating": 10, "date": "2025-10-26", "title": null, "content": "I finally saw (for me) the most anticipated film of the year, Kleber Mendon\u00e7a's best-and I like them all. Despite having read about it and seen the trailers, the film still surprised me. The final scenes moved me, something I hadn't experienced with his other films. Wagner Moura has an absurd, magnetic stage presence. Unpredictable, funny, disconcerting, and moving, The Secret Agent manages to convey the Brazilian soul on screen-quite a feat. All the countless characters are rich, captivating. A masterpiece, worthy of all the awards it has received and may yet receive."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "a42cc884-853d-4560-9acd-427cb3bf045a", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.258375", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "bdbd8656beeca33dd906e2eec95e7bc8f621f57831807cfa4786b1ee76d121b0"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "nicolasroop", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-12-23", "title": null, "content": "I really wanted to enjoy this film more than I did. The acting is good, the story is interesting enough to watch, the grindhouse/vintage style of filming was intriguing. So, what went wrong?\n\nWell for starters, the film is about 45 minutes longer than it should be. There was multiple occasions I kept asking myself \"why was this scene included in the film?\" and most of the time, the scene never connects to rest of the film. It's screams extra just to be extra. Somewhere in the middle the film loses it's grip and doesn't regain it until the last 20 minutes or so. With some tighter editing, this could have been a great film!\n\nOther than that, my only complaint is how hyped up the violence was and people calling it disturbing. We've seen worse done to better people on screen. It was nothing to write home about. In fact, I found the scene to be hilarious considering what was being done and to whom. An absolute riot of an ending, it's too bad what follows in the small epilogue is kind of depressing. Had the chance to end it on a higher note but, like most movies these days, it ends on a sour note.\n\nOverall, not a bad film. It's actually very good if you ignore that the film meanders quite a bit and that causes the enormous runtime to feel bloated and unnecessary in parts. I would recommend it, but it's a tough recommendation due to it's length. If you do see it, just be advised, it's a long film.\n\n3 dirty cops out of 5."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "a1d6ed1e-6bf1-42f5-8816-f627759b127a", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.258375", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "5650738996db6aed6c2a3b3f5d8ebe5a3b377f0e10a5ce20003f24186d375e83"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "chanzel", "rating": 5, "date": "2025-12-15", "title": null, "content": "A movie lacking coherence, full of unnecessary scenes not contributing to the main story, loose ends, and flaws. A movie that is not even entertaining since nothing really happens during the first 90 minutes. It felt like a school child put the script together to attract superficial international audiences with the additional explicit violence and sex, an unnecessary \"eternal victim\" scene, and poorly linked \"sensitive\" topics (dictatorship, refugees, slavery, corruption, neoliberal foreign extraction, reconciliation). This movie feels artificial and forced, and fails to convey a heartfelt story like \"I'm still here\" did."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "3116196a-1647-44ea-ba7e-00b70d9dcd22", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.258375", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "88d4096892efa1d68360e47a612e8ffde1791b7de9003836d1b7888bf0f06849"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "TheBigSick", "rating": null, "date": "2025-12-15", "title": null, "content": "The Secret Agent delivers a visually rich and ambitious political thriller set in Brazil during the late 1970s under a repressive military dictatorship. The film immerses you in its atmospheric period world, with a compelling central performance and a story that blends political tension, personal stakes, and moments of surreal intensity.\n\nThat said, the first and especially the second parts of the movie feel a bit loose and slow, taking their time to establish characters and context in a way that may test some viewers' patience. The pacing in these sections drifts and can feel unfocused.\n\nHowever, the third part is intense and gripping, with dramatic escalation and emotional weight that make the earlier buildup feel worthwhile. This structural imbalance is the main reason I rate it 7/10 - a solid and memorable film with a powerful climax, but one that could have benefited from tighter momentum in its early stretches."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "d6a62ff5-8d2a-4ba4-bd9d-79518e4108a1", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.258375", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "1ac4809570b5a2b20b6beaaf61407b9363ece4ef1dc53f34cf36ea3f2ce27cfc"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "sleeplest", "rating": 9, "date": "2025-12-01", "title": null, "content": "The charm of this nearly three-hour, sprawling film is that, despite my complete lack of understanding of the causes and consequences -- due to my unfamiliarity with both the director and Brazilian history -- I found myself watching it with great interest. The inherent fascination of the human interactions is embedded within the narrative yet beyond simply telling the story. This might be the best illustration of the difference between \"narrative\" and \"storytelling\". The dialogue is extensive but never tiresome or wordy, which is a rare treat among the selection of films at this year's festival."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "aac70152-34e1-42de-babc-52529b482022", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.258375", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "8e1aaf87a8979b3349ca94d8af35f4f8a627fdafa1ed77a82d69a592ebb3312c"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "adrianovasconcelos", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-12-01", "title": null, "content": "I like Director Kleber Mendon\u00e7a Filho, who doubles up as script writer in AGENTE SECRETO. He pulls no punches when it comes to depicting reality in his beloved Brazil.\n\nOver the course of its 160 minutes, AGENTE SECRETO portrays three men in the Solim\u00f5es family of Brazil's Pernambuco State who have experienced in different ways the evils of dictatorship, with Wagner Moura delivering yet another magnificent performance as each of those men in their generation.\n\nAs other reviewers point out, this is an account of events in Brazil at a difficult time when dictatorship reigned over that marvellous and multicultured land, and Mendon\u00e7a Filho hides no details hard to admit about one's country.\n\nThe dialogue floats from apparently normal conversation among common people to a growing realization that everyone is under threat. Photographs of then Brazilian dictatorial President Ernesto Geisel and other senior government officials hang in just about every office, corrupt policemen give cover to hitmen, welcome bribes and keep breaking the law.\n\nIn a film where you also get the amiable soul of Brazilians, the contrast comes from the main villain, the wealthy company owner Ghirotti well played by Luciano Chirolli, who wants university professor/researcher Solim\u00f5es I's patent, and centralization of the university funding and operation.\n\nThat contrast also hits home with raw, at times exceedingly violent action, where JAWS (yes, the Spielberg-directed 1975 film) has a double with a human leg in it, and the supernatural intervenes as that leg suddenly comes alive, becomes hairy - kids laugh about comic pictures of the \"hairy leg\" in newspapers - and starts kicking people engaging in sex, and other compromising positions. A black Angolan woman displaying an excellent, just perfect diction of Portuguese Portuguese, keeps the residents at Solim\u00f5es II's place informed about that leg. Why she and her husband appear in the film only baffled me, as they do not add to the narrative or action, other than they fled Angola and are on their way to Sweden.\n\nThe animistic, supernatural element also comes in with a scarecrow-like masked man on the side of a Pernambuco country road, which revisits Solim\u00f5es II in his nightmares.\n\nAdd to that a cat with two faces and four eyes, at least two blind. One can interpret that in various ways. I see it as symbolizing the many angles of history and human memory.\n\nConstantly in the background of dictatorial Brazil of the 1970s, the government poses an elusive but real and constant threat to all citizens.\n\nUltimately, nothing is sacred: two young girls are listening to tape recordings of Solim\u00f5es II interviewed by a woman called Elza. How and why they have that supposedly personal and secret material, who they are - neither is a relative of the Solim\u00f5es - and work for, is not disclosed but they have very modern high quality computers, so they are current generation.\n\nA positive note emerges toward the end, with Solim\u00f5es III at the helm of a blood donor unit, symbolizing the heart of Brazil pumping in spite of all menaces and democratic hiccups.\n\nSuperb period reconstruction - plenty of lovely VW Beetles, and other 1960s/70s vehicles on show - only heightens the enormous quality of Evgenia Alexandrova's cinematography, backed by highly effective editing by Matheus Farias and Eduardo Serrano.\n\nI sincerely believe AGENTE SECRETO and actor Wagner Moura deserve Academy Award nominations as Best Foreign Film and Best Actor, respectively. 8/10."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "63df2ce6-26cc-44a3-88e7-73d089211163", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.258375", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "92fe905547f1d73275dad6b4de946bb5c382f6a87f06a8282d1544e459430589"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "bruno_cpc85", "rating": 10, "date": "2025-11-29", "title": null, "content": "Kleber Mendon\u00e7a Filho builds The Secret Agent as a film that initially resembles a political thriller about Brazil's military dictatorship, but whose emotional and formal core lies in the realm of memory. Not just historical memory, but personal, family and collective memories that the country repeatedly allows to vanish. Armando/Marcelo is not simply a victim of the regime; he is a man trying to rescue the image of his mother from oblivion while the nation systematically erases whatever does not suit its official narrative. This intimate, almost archaeological search places the protagonist in a space where memory and identity merge. Mendon\u00e7a reinforces this dimension by structuring the film as a mosaic of small recollections, fragments of popular culture, everyday gestures, urban legends and social scars that turn Recife into a living repository of memory. Every detail works as a record of something that endures despite Brazil's historical negligence. Visually striking and supported by strong performances, especially from Wagner Moura, the film understands that remembering is not a passive act. It is confrontation. It is accepting that not everything can be recovered, and that Brazilian memory is shaped as much by what survives as by what slips away. By avoiding easy resolutions and refusing the conventional closure expected from genre cinema, The Secret Agent makes clear that its goal is not to solve a mystery but to expose a country deeply uncomfortable with its own past. In the end, the film reveals itself to be far less about espionage and far more about the imperfect effort to reconstruct stories that were almost lost."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "675f60c8-baa9-4b18-b767-465bef2791a8", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.258901", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "e7ecc1da1e85e43789e1b35cf6a7a6b0407c0e8c4dca339b47914394df70a305"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "gustborges", "rating": 10, "date": "2025-11-03", "title": null, "content": "This is a masterpiece and definitely Kleber Mendon\u00e7a Filho's best film - what a fantastic career so far! I was moved by Wagner Mouras' performance. The film can feel a bit slow in the beginning as many characters are included in the scene without much explanation but all those moving parts start to make sense gradually in a steadily growing storyline. I highly recommend you watch the film without descriptions, spoilers or even watching the trailer so you linger a bit more in the dark, trying to anchor to Kleber's few hints until the story is fully exposed."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "5855a759-74a4-4971-b974-439b2b4d31a1", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.258901", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "251f7eb167d38e34993ebe9eca7302950aae028358294d21e0c7fc0566e39e5f"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "josiahplatte", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-10-23", "title": null, "content": "So frustrating, this movie had a lot of potential. Opening was great, cinematography and color are beautiful, cast is great, acting is great, but it was ruined in the editing. It's just too long, an hour needed to be cut. I also failed to see how the title correlated with the film at all. The best part about this film is it reminded me how good narcos is."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "d8932caf-8493-44bf-b003-3e4f84b75a1f", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.258901", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "113f83754fea66e92e29de194355eb79424d6aa86c025f76cb504e8d0a48fd74"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "willisthetall", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-10-20", "title": null, "content": "The Secret Agent is a captivating movie and an excellent contender of Brazil for Best International Feature (maybe even Best Actor to Wagner Moura too). It has storytelling as its biggest quality, but, despite being a very good movie, it also has its minor flaws.\n\nMarcelo's story is told in a fragmented way. The spectator sees him in 1977 during the first and the second act and, just after this, we see why he is in that situation. It all (along with other elements, like direction) make his story (which, honestly, is not so \"wow\") more interesting.\n\nMy only complaint is the second act, which is way too long. I just felt something could be shortened to make the film more \"optimized\". It's not a big problem, it's nothing that can make a person stop wanting to watch.\n\nMarcelo's plot is not the only one here, there is a smaller storyline that serves to link the movie to the present days and to give a finale to the main story. It's not exactly a complaint, but I found this second story ill-fitted. I would make some changes, like NOT fragment it throughout the movie (like Kleber Mendon\u00e7a did).\n\nOverall, this is a very good film. I travelled far to watch this movie before everyone in Rio de Janeiro Int'l Film Festival and, fortunately, I didn't have any regrets."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "be6689aa-fd35-4e20-817f-01f0a3a159a4", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.258901", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "326adb40cad01e258f37e1aaac75da652b794a1a53aae17ec4b6c02713ddd5ce"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "elizagalo", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-11-03", "title": null, "content": "The film is nice but a good edition would cut it to 1 hour less at least. The start is fool of prosaicism that is not even good entreteiniment. After a long prelude the movie finally starts and is actually very dynamic and interesting. My frustration about it is that some ends are not explored giving me the impression a watched a documentary more than a film."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "8c9c77dc-94ff-4f21-81dd-7c2c98c058f9", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.258901", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "c2deb01b9808280a57b33d01787354ee37a6511d6a070fc712732ce6f289d1d8"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "teufreitas", "rating": 10, "date": "2025-11-20", "title": null, "content": "Not so easy to categorize this movie. Even though mystery threads through the entire story, The Secret Agent expands far beyond genre. Comedy, folklore, political critique, historical reconstruction and intimate drama crash into one another with intention, giving the film a bold, high-energy identity that refuses to sit still. Kleber Mendon\u00e7a Filho crafts a deeply personal narrative rooted in Recife, each chapter functioning like a self-contained regional myth filled with allegories, tension and cultural memory.\n\nWagner Moura is outstanding as Marcelo, a tech professor who returns to his hometown while running from a violent past in S\u00e3o Paulo. As he tries to protect his young son Fernando, he finds refuge with Dona Sebastiana, played with luminous warmth by T\u00e2nia Maria. She becomes the film's emotional anchor, embodying the maternal, welcoming force that shelters the marginalized and turns pain into community.\n\nThe film doesn't avoid Brazil's open wounds. A chapter referencing the death of a child in 2020 and another confronting blatant academic xenophobia reveal how Mendon\u00e7a Filho uses these stories not as exposition, but as lived reminders of what the country still refuses to face. Marcelo's search for any document that proves his mother existed becomes a metaphor for a broader national amnesia: the memories erased, the histories neglected, the identities lost under the weight of time and authoritarianism.\n\nYou'll frustrate yourself expecting a conventional thriller or a spy narrative. This is something else entirely: a film that goes full throttle in its ideas, trusting its striking cinematography and daring screenplay to shape an experience far from formula, the work of a director at his most confident.\n\nAn ode to memory: the ones we chase, the ones we distort, and the ones that disappear if no one insists on remembering. When Fernando admits he no longer remembers his father, the film quietly lands its message: Marcelo is a Secret Agent because he was forgotten, and forgetting isn't just personal, it's national."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "687e0ee2-fd42-4d82-88bb-e1d9d13742c7", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.258901", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "316601a3f9d0605bfe8582f27a9f14bf9ce15540b551e9847a76afaee3238309"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "jgcorrea", "rating": 7, "date": "2025-11-17", "title": null, "content": "The title is as misleading as it is abstract. Or rather, 'Secret Agent' is not in itself an abstract phrase. It could refer, for example, to James Bond. But the relationship between this title and the content of this film is indeed abstract. \"Passive Agent\" would be a better title, meaning (in grammar) \"complement of efficient cause.\" Lacking a plot, why so many subplots? Why a redundant and expletive epilogue? On the plus side, \"The Secret Agent\" is an interesting allegory about official archives, silencing, and contested memory. The film highlights the important role of digging, connecting the dots, reading \"against the grain,\" and questioning official discourses in order to uncover suppressed narratives."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "a77f8d88-642c-4935-89d7-65b728abd721", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.258901", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "4e64b7d135f19bb06101bed7b2e76146b053686b7ebce2e7628dc6dc402220e3"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "Hildebrando_Martins_Almeida", "rating": 2, "date": "2026-01-21", "title": null, "content": "This review is written by a Brazilian cinephile. The fact that this is a national production does not impose on me any obligation to offer automatic praise, nor does it lead me to overlook flaws in the name of cultural patriotism. For me, cinema is, above all, precision, coherence, and narrative rigor. Having watched nearly seven thousand films over several decades - not counting the many titles revisited multiple times - I feel fully justified in offering a frank and uncompromising analysis, regardless of a film's country of origin. The Secret Agent (2025) was my first encounter with the work of Kleber Mendon\u00e7a Filho, and unfortunately it resulted in deep disappointment.\n\nThe film presents itself as a political thriller set in 1977, during Brazil's military dictatorship, but stumbles precisely where it should be most solid: narrative clarity, internal coherence, and dramatic discipline. From the opening moments, there is a tendency toward redundant symbolism. The decision to show full-screen photographs of artists who were prominent in Brazil in 1977 clearly aims to anchor the story in its historical period. However, only moments later, a title card explicitly states that the story takes place in 1977. The effect is unnecessary and weakens the introduction, as if the film felt compelled to overemphasize something already established.\n\nThe gas station sequence exemplifies another recurring issue: the sacrifice of plausibility in favor of blunt allegory. Armando arrives at the station and there is a corpse abandoned beside it, exposed in the open air. Even after two policemen arrive, the body is ignored; one of them prefers to question Armando and search his car. Even considering the authoritarian context of the era, this situation is unacceptable from a basic standpoint of realism: a decomposing body would produce a strong odor, pose sanitary risks, and require immediate removal. Everything suggests that the corpse was deliberately left there as a symbolic representation of death made banal under the dictatorship. If that was the intention, the result is misguided and excessive, as it breaks the internal logic of the scene and undermines credibility.\n\nDuring the opening credits, the film briefly cuts away from Wagner Moura inside the car to return to the image of the corpse lying on the dirt. This repetition adds no new meaning, deepens no metaphor, and advances nothing narratively. It is merely another visual underline that reinforces the impression of empty insistence.\n\nThe screenplay's structure weakens further with the abrupt introduction, around the 43-minute mark, of two young women sitting in front of laptops, listening to cassette tapes labeled with the year 1977 and the name Marcelo. The scene interrupts the main narrative without any explanation. We do not know who these women are, what time period they belong to, or how they relate to Armando. Only at the end of the film, when one of them speaks with a doctor - Armando's son - does it become clear that they are students researching the dictatorship era and the events surrounding Armando. This information, deliberately withheld, does not generate productive mystery; it merely causes confusion. A brief contextualization at the beginning would have sufficed. As presented, the scene feels intrusive and poorly integrated.\n\nAnother example of narrative excess is the scene involving the German tailor Hans, played by Udo Kier. The character adds nothing to the plot, clarifies no relationships, and advances no conflict. It is a sterile detour that merely extends the runtime. The impression is that of a personal concession by the director to the actor, who passed away in November 2025, but cinema cannot be sustained by implicit tributes. Notably, Armando himself seems to share the viewer's boredom, leaving the scene without even acknowledging the delegate. Several similar moments appear throughout the film, scenes that exist without clear dramatic function.\n\nTo be fair, the period reconstruction is impeccable. In this respect, the film deserves genuine praise. Cars, costumes, hairstyles, portraits of President Geisel on the walls, and the films playing in theaters in 1977 all demonstrate meticulous research and attention to detail. Unfortunately, this visual rigor contrasts sharply with a basic problem in the dialogue: imprecise diction. At several points, lines are difficult to understand, which further compromises an already confusing narrative.\n\nInformation gaps multiply. In the secret meeting between Armando and Elza and Valdemar inside a movie theater, nothing is explained. Who are these people? What is their concrete relationship to Armando? Why are they recording the conversation? The film offers no sufficient clues for the viewer to construct meaning, treating the scene as if its importance were self-evident.\n\nThe most problematic - and frankly embarrassing - moment occurs around the 1h49 mark, in the infamous leg sequence. Grandiose music accompanies the image of a severed leg lying on a lawn. This is followed by nighttime scenes in a public square where several people engage in sex as if it were an improvised outdoor brothel. The same leg appears walking among them. A cut shows a woman reading a newspaper article about the incident, oddly describing it as a \"shadow\" rather than a leg. Returning to the square, the leg begins attacking people. What had been, however flawed, a political drama suddenly veers into grotesque horror. The sequence is absurd, tonally incoherent, and ridiculous. Later we learn it is the same leg found inside a shark and stolen from the morgue by a corrupt policeman, who throws it into a river. If the goal was to make it disappear, throwing it into a river where it could float and be found again is an elementary contradiction. The film ends without ever clarifying the leg's narrative or symbolic relevance.\n\nThe musical score and incidental music further aggravate the experience. They are intrusive, excessively dramatic, and emotionally manipulative, often at odds with the images. Rather than sustaining tension, they generate fatigue and irritation.\n\nLogical inconsistencies pile up in the final act. When Armando asks the delegate for help, he manages to identify Vilmar, the hired killer. Yet Marcelo points him out to the police while the man is shown from behind, talking on the phone, even though moments earlier Marcelo had not seen his face and had only been called by name. Soon after, Vilmar phones Augusto Borba, who answers at the beach near a public phone. How did the assassin know where to find him? After killing two policemen, Vilmar escapes and passes right by the officer guarding the entrance gate, who inexplicably lets him go.\n\nIn the ensuing chase, Abdias, Borba's partner, pursues Vilmar. A seated bystander, upon noticing a bloodstain on the ground, spontaneously tells Abdias which direction the killer went. How did he know Abdias was chasing the murderer? After Abdias is killed, a newspaper reports that he was shot twice in the face, while the film clearly shows a single shot from behind. The same newspaper also gives the delegate's name as Leonardo Ferreira Monteiro, even though throughout the film he is identified as Euclides Cavalcanti. These are gross errors, difficult to excuse.\n\nEven the film's title is misleading. The Secret Agent suggests that Armando is some sort of clandestine operative, when in fact he is an ordinary citizen. One cannot expect viewers to know that during the dictatorship the term was informally used to describe unidentified agents linked to the regime. That context should be made clear within the film itself.\n\nUnanswered questions abound: Who is Jo\u00e3o Pedro, who appears to be Armando's superior? Who is the businessman Henrique Ghirotti? Why does he hire Augusto Borba and Abdias to kill Armando, when it is Armando who seems to harbor deep hatred toward Ghirotti? The logic behind the central motivations remains obscure.\n\nMarceloThe Secret AgentMarcelo ends as it begins: laden with symbolic pretensions but lacking narrative cohesion, dramatic clarity, and internal rigor. What could have been a sharp portrait of a dark chapter in Brazilian history dissolves into a collection of poorly articulated scenes, exaggerated allegories, and basic screenplay errors. The final impression is not one of productive unease, but of perplexity and exhaustion. A film that demands much from its audience, yet offers very little in return."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "a2bdcd8c-da0d-4374-9774-670e7aa84354", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.258901", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "fb0cec29bae89847a21ef573f7d25c338edf9588abf701a37128a77d6cb48dba"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "guisreis", "rating": 9, "date": "2025-11-29", "title": null, "content": "In my opinion, it is the best movie by Kleber Mendon\u00e7a Filho so far (even better than Bacurau and short film Recife Frio). It has an outstanding casting, and the script, instead of an economic approach of including only scenes which are directly connected to the ending, has as a major concern showing the environment. The movie is colourful while addresses very sinister violent events, is merges absurd fantasy with political thriller, it contrasts carnival with the dark tentacles of the military authoritarian regime. Interestingly, the focus is not in institutionalized coertion. The despicable policemen, who hate communists and murder and hide the bodies without any concern, show themselves as incoherent multilayered people, able to do horrible things, for sure, but far from being pure evil. Indeed, the true villains in the film are certainly related to the dictatorship and to those cops, but they move in the shadows (although not always worried about veing fragrant), on the fringes of the slaughter-friendly regime. The university and the public interest are the ones who the greedy opportunistic villains attack in order to profit at the cost of the very country. The highest villains are spread along the different classes, and the most rich they are, the most coward too, increasing profit and reducing risks through outsourced dirty job. The good people may not succeed in a harsh realistic tale, many stories may be forgotten and erased, but the heroes may be anyone, as Sebastiana makes it clear."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "5edd9d3d-0160-48fb-88d3-162698a52f43", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.258901", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "10daf5a95e46c76e57d8db9e0af3e536fa341cb22b87860b191b6466d652b5ce"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "chezztone", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-11-08", "title": null, "content": "I enjoyed this movie (despite its length, and I usually have a short attention span) and would like to see it again. It is an actors' film, full of great performances. The details of the period and locale seem perfect, it pulls you in. Friends who lived through the Brazilian dictatorship say this film captures the feeling of people disappearing for no reason, strange things happening without explanation.\n\nThere are quite a few important parts that I just don't understand, or maybe they are supposed to be open to interpretation."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "1ebee13b-8ca8-443c-945e-dc8eb78d32c5", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.258901", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "b76266f18116f13f24979444e16e2c056cdb3073afe33bd4602271d447d74f3c"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "wilker-56247", "rating": 10, "date": "2025-11-13", "title": null, "content": "Fantastic!!\n\nThe Secret Agent presents Recife in the 1970s, with all its culture and its joyful people, despite the hardships they face. The film reflects a pain we still feel in Brazil today - the uncertainty about the whereabouts and reasons behind the deaths of so many people during the military repression. You can feel the care and passion of the actors, producers, and everyone involved in making this film a reality. Brazil is beautifully represented, and I truly hope it goes to the Oscars!"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "f512553a-79d0-44de-b9ae-13ab901bb0d0", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.258901", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "eecb8f50be5eeb9ef22fb9aa5501144ee05fc5e14c1753d672e160698f0812b0"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "GustavoO-70", "rating": 9, "date": "2025-11-09", "title": null, "content": "The secret agent chronicles a man trying to escape from something, from a story that is unfolding, and from a past that the protagonist, Marcelo (portrayed masterfully by the great Wagner Moura) had no choice but to face. The screenplay, written by the director himself (Kleber Mendon\u00e7a Filho), carries a unique characteristic weight, which is also seen in his other films, such as Aquarius and Bacurau; which in a way also dictates the pace of the work. It is somewhat slow, but filled with suspense, mysteries, drama, and extremely satisfying performances.\n\nIn this film, Mendon\u00e7a brings us what is most characteristic in the Brazilian person and their culture. Giving creative freedom to striking moments, such as the counting of deaths during Carnival; the extremely strong police oppression of the time; the caricatured personalities of the people, such as Ms. Sebastiana and an assassin hired in the Northeast who does things like a true \"cabra da peste\" (a Northeastern expression, loosely meaning a tough, brave, or formidable person); among others... It is an immersive film with an ending that raises questions and opens up a wide range of interpretations. Clearly a rough gem of the best of Brazilian cinema, a gift for all of us in the historical and emphatic language of Kleber Mendon\u00e7a."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "4dba9833-ffbb-48b2-9df8-2076573d1f04", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.258901", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "7ab385097c7f8705f2fe8bca6bdb6198dccd2c1bc42a262a9312573afd54eda9"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "saadanathan", "rating": 7, "date": "2025-10-14", "title": null, "content": "The Secret Agent by Kleber Mendonca Filho is a story of loss and confrontation. As the audience are feared for the protagonist's fate, looking behind their shoulder as the main character does throughout the story.\n\nThe movie in itself is well made; with local and authentic film locations in Brazil. Along with a great editing pace that doesn't feel too rushed nor slow. And with an impressive cast of actors that deliver a phenomenal and humorous performance.\n\nThe story though might be the main argument amongst critics and viewers. The story in itself is interesting: In 1977 Brazil, a technology expert returns to his hometown from fear of being assassinated over a dispute. He soon realizes he is being followed and must act before it's too late.\n\nThe story takes a long time to further develop itself; the narrative centers around Marcelo Alves (Wagner Moura) and his attempt to reconnect with his son. Then it's revealed that the people after him sent two hitmen. Perhaps halfway into the movie, the full story is revealed to the audience, with a better understanding. But by then, too much time has been put into the filler and setting.\n\nThe establishment of the characters takes too long and deviates from the central story. In the end, Marcelo's death is revealed over an article in the newspaper. His death has become anti-climatic in a way similar to Josh Brolin's character in No Country for Old Man.\n\nAside of the story deviating near the end, I still very much enjoyed the movie and its characters. With each one being unique in its own way; With Tania Maria as Dona Sebastiana being humorous and stealing the show.\n\nA powerful performance by Wagner Moura shouldn't go unnoticed either. Moura throughout the entire film is captivating and epic, ever since watching him in Narcos and Elite Squad I was invested in his career and ability to perform so well on screen.\n\nThe movie uses multiple elements to try and keep the audience invested with the story, whether with the use of animals: the two-faced cat, the dead shark with a foot inside it. Or whether with the use of movie references (Jaws being the prominent one). Yet, just like the main story; all these elements are deviating from each other, leaving more questions than answers.\n\nIn short, The Secret Agent is a movie to watch with an open mind and with patience, knowing that there was more to be desired. More left on the table to be dealt with, and perhaps that's the message behind the movie, containing the complex life in Brazil: nothing truly is settled."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "ac0234f5-27b3-4879-aaf3-9e6414050215", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.258901", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "154056e01a127d8bc7985f5576f4c0108e28ceeab0c7c8a0cad293d91f73a0af"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "LeonAL", "rating": 10, "date": "2025-11-09", "title": null, "content": "It is a challenge to describe to a common viewer the imense variety of themes (and movie genres) this film portrait. It is an ode of Brazilian culture, history and people and one of Kleber Mendon\u00e7a Filho shinier gems.\n\nComedy and Tragedy side by side Fiction and History side by side Violence and kindness side by side\n\nWagner Moura a star Tania Maria as Sebastiana a glorious and moving performance All cast at their best\n\nMemories fade and life goes on, preserve your loved ones. Filme bom da po***"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "f11465c2-3956-4ec2-b4ab-a29ae2793d52", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.258901", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "d11ddfffefe8e0c0d00c0b535febe85c6774197b0b8b4c6f2f4764c836c9b97c"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "metodico", "rating": 6, "date": "2026-01-22", "title": null, "content": "Kleber Mendon\u00e7a Filho has succeeded in maturing his filmmaking, and uses a more sophisticated language in \"The Secret Agent\" than in his previous films; the opening scene makes it clear that it will be a film that will work with subtext at various points. Despite having a well-developed subtext, \"The Secret Agent\" often feels like a film with a drawn-out script; its long duration is unnecessary, and this is evident in many moments. I don't know why many critics consider \"The Secret Agent\" a thrilling film because, for the most part, the film is slow, and not a meditative or poetic slowness, but a monotonous, everyday slowness... This may also be connected to the editing work, which could have made the film more dynamic. Despite these problems, \"The Secret Agent\" is a very interesting story about forgotten people, about crimes that are never punished, and of course, about Brazil. It's important to remember that Kleber Mendon\u00e7a Filho is a person who carries a very politicized vision in his films, and this makes them more superficial than profound. There is no great philosophical work, no reflection that truly transcends pragmatism; this is one of Kleber Mendon\u00e7a Filho's biggest flaws-being a filmmaker who looks at many things askance and forgets that the beauty of cinema lies in its richness philosophical, on the human side, in aesthetic refinement, etc..."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "02fb5218-1606-4204-87b6-2e168e69167a", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.259429", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "7118fdb14fda869fca1086063f04a8d48a9c4c8fa654453e32dc3d3e04c0aac1"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "li0904426", "rating": 9, "date": "2025-11-28", "title": null, "content": "The movie The Secret Agent is set during the 1977 Brazilian military dictatorship. It follows Marcelo, who returns home hoping to reunite with his son, only to find himself entangled in a web of political danger, corruption, and the oppressive atmosphere of the regime.\n\nThe writer and director Kleber Mendon\u00e7a Filho delivers a visually stunning film that, thanks to great production and costume design, transports us straight into the 1970s. The cinematography is another major highlight, especially with its carefully chosen color palette.\n\nOne of the movie's major problems is that Mendon\u00e7a focuses on presenting various characters and their stories that revolve around the central character, Marcelo, but neglects to explore Marcelo's own story. We learn very little about Marcelo's life, which is shown only briefly through a few flashbacks. Also, the ending of the movie doesn't have the same pace as the rest of the movie; it seems forced, vague, and uninspired.\n\nA former president of the Cannes Film Festival once said that Brazilian directors make movies mainly for Brazilians, not for the world, and Mendon\u00e7a kind of proves that. For example, in the scene where a rich woman accidentally runs over her maid's daughter, only Brazilian viewers really understand the deeper meaning behind it, while most international audiences miss it completely.\n\nStill, the movie has some great strengths: an excellent original story, a cast made mostly of non-actors, and solid, clean direction.\n\nIt's definitely worth watching!"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "d6637022-3375-44ce-868a-d433d78f0be5", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.259429", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "e994dbfa9d899346e8b3efe1a622d887cab1e3fc25a383a120b561ac424c6a85"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "minimaster-67734", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-11-24", "title": null, "content": "This film tells its story out of chronological order, and while the structure isn't too hard to follow, it doesn't create the smoothest or most natural flow. The constant shifts in time can feel a little distracting, and some viewers might find themselves less absorbed because of it.\n\nThe pacing also gets in the way. The movie starts off very slowly, almost to the point where it's hard to stay engaged, and it takes a long time before anything really starts happening. Even when the story finally gains some momentum, it never becomes especially emotional. It remains simple and grounded, which can work well for a period drama, especially one that aims for realism. And to be fair, the film does a great job capturing the look and feel of the time period with detailed, believable imagery.\n\nStill, as good as the visuals are, the story itself feels pretty thin. There isn't a lot of depth, and it's hard to feel truly connected to what's going on. Because of that, the movie ends up being more impressive to look at than enjoyable to watch.\n\nOne creative choice that doesn't land very well is using the same actor to play both the father and, years later, the son. It's a bold idea, but it comes across as a bit clich\u00e9 and doesn't really add anything meaningful to the story. If anything, it pulls you out of the experience.\n\nOverall, this period drama is well-made and visually strong, but its pacing, plot, and character choices leave plenty of room for improvement."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "dc50a861-2036-4e0a-a484-cb0fdfb40d51", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.259429", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "c9601af37705cb4f4d77fcdea9d626b03da3099a7e7e684a773cdd4a5a4835a6"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "hugomisurelli", "rating": 2, "date": "2025-12-18", "title": null, "content": "Too long, simplistic script. Extremely boring and long. Confusing and simplistic script, 60 minutes would have been enough for a slightly better rating. Unfortunately, not even Wagner Moura's performance saves it. The film's slow pace ultimately results in a disconnect between the various stages of the film. A waste of time."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "32fafbeb-64ce-4327-903b-76bf5a37dc1d", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.259429", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "1b83ec51900fac5cbe6490bad068905de6a38ad5666173517228dc47dba0424d"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "calcrj", "rating": 10, "date": "2025-11-24", "title": null, "content": "\"The Secret Agent\" is a movie I recently watched at the Brazilian Film Festival. Before diving into the storyline, I must caution you-this is absolutely not suitable for children or for anyone sensitive to graphic content. The film contains harrowing murders toward the conclusion, and its tone is undeniably bleak... as intended.\n\nThe narrative unfolds in Brazil during the 1970s, a time when the country was under military rule since 1964. The police are portrayed uniformly as corrupt and malicious. One of their targets is a man who, as you discover, has committed no crime whatsoever-he simply crossed paths with a powerful and ruthless figure. Much of the film follows his attempts to remain hidden while vicious pursuers hunt him down.\n\nIs this the formula for a lighthearted movie? Certainly not. But it is skillfully crafted and sheds light on a historical era many may not be familiar with-but should be. It's a well-executed, somber film that may leave you emotionally exhausted once the credits roll."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "70b84e77-132c-4406-bcd9-4a8686831497", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.259429", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "d1572e34514864e22cad28079c306a2c9be44d0c72dccabbb4f0ee843060c2ca"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "DrGadimov", "rating": 10, "date": "2026-01-05", "title": null, "content": "Incredible movie set in 1977 Brazil dictatorship-corruption, police brutality, moral collapse everywhere (that shark leg scene is perfect satire). Armando on the run, mystery kept me hooked until reveals. Slow first half builds tension perfectly. Themes of resistance, fear, lost humanity hit hard. Wagner Moura amazing. Tiny issue: early slow burn, but worth it. Deserves all awards-perfect 10/10."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "57afa024-6116-430d-a1f7-a31f23ec444a", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.259429", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "21a245c4ef30232d6b6081d79ecb1ffa48d469a8fcacdc36715d30ebc143cd30"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "AlissonYamakawa", "rating": 10, "date": "2025-12-18", "title": null, "content": "Forget what you think a \"political thriller\" should be. The Secret Agent is not what you think-it's something better. Visually and dramatically, it is breathtaking.\n\nI understand some audiences may find it too long or frustrating due to its measured pacing, extended silences, unresolved ending, and complex non-linear narrative. Yet as a slow-burn thriller, it is exceptionally well-directed, edited, and acted.\n\nDirector Kleber Mendon\u00e7a Filho has not made a simple political thriller; he has created something completely new. He masterfully mixes suspense, dark comedy, hints of fantasy, and western, all infused with the unique spirit and specific cultural elements of Brazil's Northeast. This makes for a work that will be discussed by film lovers and historians for years to come.\n\nThe result is a work of staggering originality and depth. The cast, with Wagner Moura at the forefront, delivers performances tuned perfectly to the film's shifting tones-grounded and gritty one moment, theatrically expressive the next."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "c7191cc7-b38b-4ed5-acce-4bd49b5dc0f4", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.259429", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "d91478e70a5a86d8c175d5587897a5f0922cb4ae06eda593eb2e761a2253e2eb"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "wanessasantana", "rating": 9, "date": "2025-11-18", "title": null, "content": "Kleber making history again, a film rich in analogies, based on the past to portray the present. A film full of irony, playing with the very seriousness of the unjust situation that Armando is experiencing. I fell in love with the supporting actors, especially Dona Sebastiana, a character so real that I find myself wanting to know every stage of her life. I have nothing more to say about the film, it explains itself. The ending is literally reality, without adding or taking away anything. I am proud to witness this spectacle, the same feeling I had with \"I'm Still Here,\" it's not a film made to reach first place in awards, but made for us Brazilians and necessary so that we don't forget this period of our history."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "8769f90a-0ff0-481b-8a86-789734fa3171", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.259429", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "3385da842e97d390893f939b0171aeac644207015fa16f5acde4dc2ffd23d6ec"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "ChiefBogeyman", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-11-10", "title": null, "content": "We understand from the first scene of a gas station and dead body that this is not a 'serious' film. It is a Brasilian story and in that regard needs to interpreted with that cultural and historical context. Hairy legs, Carnival death tolls, police chief's, a home for refugees, free sex all make for a 1970 political telenovela set in Recife. This is not a slow burn, it is just slow with lots of useless set pieces which look great but don't propell the story further. The film did win the best director and best actor award in Cannes which are both very much influenced by the jury and not necessarily by their abilities even though Wagner Moura is outstanding as always. Don't listen to critics, the film is just okay."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "6d1cdcbc-d7aa-48a4-93f4-6a019657a084", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.259429", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "3419bcea1abb0138dc3eccc6d5b9aaf3445a5406fbaccc1f66bca663c70d3af1"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "DanielA-9432", "rating": 9, "date": "2025-11-20", "title": null, "content": "Despite its many scenes of violence - served in a myriad of flavors through the characters' interactions - The Secret Agent remains a powerful and refreshing tale about Brazil. Even though the long shadow of the dictatorship may linger overhead, the film itself is not concerned with offering, nor pretending to offer, any deep political critique. It is a light, absorbing, and savory story about the nation's people, rich enough to remind Brazilian viewers of all the spices, sauces, and recipes that have shaped - and still shape - its society.\n\nFor those who have never visited Brazil or befriended a Brazilian, the pace at which scenes shift and tensions dissolve may feel, at first, strange or slow to digest. But once you locate yourself within this surreal experience, you may realize you're standing before a mirror - one in which you recognize yourself in the characters who struck you the most and will soon miss as the movie goes by.\n\nMuch like violence in Brazil, climaxes that are patiently built simply dissipate into the surreal haze of what living in Brazil is. The resolutions of these tensions, though carefully constructed, are neither moving nor shocking nor thrilling. Mendon\u00e7a seems to do this deliberately, and that is perhaps the film's only deep message: what should move or shock you most is sacrificed, almost nullified, in favor of a smooth yet desensitized belief that life must go on - that it's just another Thursday.\n\nThe final scenes, little more than a sub-subplot, showcase this once more for the viewer who might have missed the message. Without those, one must be sensitive enough to detect the kind of insensitivity that survival quietly demands."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "8f1b2514-b0c5-4628-9e0a-8db84e19eada", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.259955", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "39ea51c856004f1480e16a842a66ed0fd3ebfbfeeee25a745ba8808cb383838c"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "saolivaresm", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-01-25", "title": null, "content": "Brazilian director Kleber Mendon\u00e7a Filho writes and directs this thriller that reflects the dictatorship in Brazil. A period drama that evolves into a gripping historical portrait of a dark period in Brazilian society.\n\nStarring an impeccable Wagner Moura, the film is set in 1977, during Brazil's military dictatorship. Marcelo, a teacher trying to escape a turbulent past, returns to the city of Recife hoping for a fresh start and to reunite with his son. However, he soon discovers that the city is far from the refuge he imagined, as government forces are hunting him and death threats hang over him.\n\nThe accolades are more than well-deserved for *O Agente Secreto*, a powerful film that, beneath the urban legend, hides a human thriller about daily life in Brazil during the dictatorship. It's a story about a community that offers a narratively complex yet highly engaging tale. The film navigates genres with ease, resulting in an explosive and delightful mix of drama, crime, thriller, and even giallo, with well-placed doses of humor.\n\nIt's a thriller that needs time to reveal its true nature. Between the darkness of its characters and the folly of their surroundings, the film conceals an intense protagonist with whom you gradually become involved, feeling like you're part of this entire survival journey. It goes far beyond what its title suggests and offers different interpretations, not only of what happened at that specific moment, but also before and after.\n\nA vigorous and genuine exercise in pure genre, inspired and captivating. Few filmmakers today manage to transport us to a time, a place, and stories that ignite fascination, where each character conceals an intriguing plot waiting to be uncovered. It overflows with a contagious, anarchic energy while portraying the rot of the dictatorship and conveying a profound love for Brazil, its history, its customs, and, of course, for cinema itself. Kleber Mendon\u00e7a Filho stands out for his intelligence in every sense and surrounds himself with a cast that gives their all on screen, ensuring that we never feel the film is forced, but rather that it's a story that envelops us like the most gripping intrigue before our eyes.\n\nIt's a charming film that doesn't strive for perfection as its greatest achievement, but rather finds in its humanity a way to transform its flaws into great virtues. Its uniqueness accompanies a hypnotic narrative that moves between the passage of time and the present day. It's a work that doesn't hide its message and dares to offer its own version of a part of Brazilian history, a proposition that proves more than satisfactory."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "c4b808f7-8901-4cf9-86d4-e7858e81bbba", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.259955", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "a89876dadadd2a4c317a97168e9493cf50afbec0ff254f2fb80db038b3df0d98"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "RaidonA", "rating": 9, "date": "2026-01-24", "title": null, "content": "This film is superb. I would recommend reading about it before watching, as being able to recognize the complex political context, brilliant nods to Brazilian folklore, etc will make the viewing more enjoyable and easier to understand scenes that may come across random or unnecessary that contribute to a deep story drenched in the complicated and impactful reality of Brazil's history and present times. The cinematography, humour, soundtrack and bright colours of costumes and set bring the same level of complexity as the politics and violence to the visual front."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "53d2c3df-f23f-4e86-bfcf-98d6229d6c0c", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.259955", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "390ff7e315ffb8f2d0737b39394620b0a4eacdc24b9d01828fe7314c691542c8"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "renatolgtr", "rating": null, "date": "2026-01-26", "title": null, "content": "The king is naked but everybody's saying that his clothes are the bomb, so you go with the flow. People are misunderstandig lack of good storytelling and cinema technic with \"art\".\n\nI love Kurosawa, Koreeda, Sofia Coppola, no problem at all with \"slow\" or \"dense\" movies.\n\nAs a brazilian speaker the acting is laughable. Remove Wagner and Maria Fernanda C\u00e2ndido and you have a really lame cast, that may sound ok for non-portuguese speakers.\n\nI've lost almost 3 hours, ain't gonna lose a minute more : be advised, it is a semi-amateur movie (heavy) lobbied as \"art\"."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "66ade1a0-eee7-44c2-a47b-f58b54509242", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.259955", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "45fb7a5e49a63a0ec5d8d38bf2e2174e005fce4818f0f0f10e52d32952a6bd43"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "flicklover", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-01-07", "title": null, "content": "I had not even heard of The Secret Agent. I hadn't even seen a trailer and had to go to the ONE theater that was playing this film 50 miles away! But I was intrigued by the buzz around this film. Being a Brazilian film that was directed by Kleber Mendon\u00e7a Filho I thought it was going to be great. Last year's great Brazilian film I'm Still Here which was one of the best films I saw made me go into this film with very high expectations.\n\nI have to say that even though I liked the film I was disappointed because I thought I would see a much better film. It is set in Brazil in 1977 during the Brazilian military dictatorship. Armando, played by Wagner Moura is a former professor who is fleeing persecution from the regime. He arrives in Recife to gets an apartment from a woman who gives shelter to various political refugees. Armando tries to reconnect with his son which had been raised by his in laws since his wife had died. Armando is in hiding because he's in danger and has to leave Brazil. All of this would be a lot more intriguing if the film was more focused. It is technically a thriller but director Kleber Mendon\u00e7a Filho makes this film more about a collection of weird and quirky characters and a more satirical tone at times that reduce the tension. But the film feels more like a love letter to films the fire tor loves. There is a focus on Jaws, for instance that in many ways is a metaphor for what Armando is going through. Also, Sr. Alexandre, Armando's father in law is a projectionust at a Recife movie theater. There are so e great scenes there. Including huge line outside a showing of Jaws, and the audience reaction to The Omen. There's a plot point about a severed leg found in a shark that gets a lot of attention. Even a very funny dream sequence with that leg. Very funny scene but it breaks what should be a more compelling and tense story. When the 3rd act comes, there is some tension but not nearly as much as if it could have been there if the film has been more focused.\n\nAlso, at almost 160 minutes the film is very slow.\n\nGood film, not as good as it could have been\n\nGrade: B-"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "6dae1084-b08e-4b31-8b13-7ec285bcf6ef", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.259955", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "e79874aef131b5cfb74e66792cd3e7c70e71558de0ca665f2b6424d1371624fc"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "lukemindlin", "rating": 3, "date": "2025-12-08", "title": null, "content": "This movie was a menagerie of nonsense and uninteresting storylines about an era of politics that was made to feel uninteresting and disconnected. It fails to feel engaging. It fails to deliver what felt like a cohesive story. And it was way too long with what felt like a constant slog of just living in this world that offers no payoff. The acting was fine, but I don't understand the hype. I really disliked this film."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "9535cd87-7492-4e0f-bf21-0c6e83ec0001", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.259955", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "9e5f6da9cdf0fad798a9b4369ebaef4f2fcf8f789dde773a26eafe58724fcb47"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "vilhenafurlan", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-11-09", "title": null, "content": "Set against the tense atmosphere of Brazil in 1977, \"Secret Agent\" follows Fernando, a man in his forties who moves to Recife in an attempt to escape his troubled past.\n\nThe film's narrative is intriguing and highly subjective, skillfully using the \"show, don't tell\" approach. This makes the story feel deeper and more realistic, allowing the audience to interpret emotions and events for themselves.\n\nWagner Moura delivers an outstanding performance, portraying Fernando as an introspective and complex character. His subtle gestures and expressions convey emotion and inner conflict without relying on dialogue.\n\nThe film's cinematography and color palette effectively capture the oppressive social atmosphere of the time, adding depth to the story's tone.\n\nHowever, the film does have its flaws. The soundtrack feels too subdued, adding little emotion to the scenes, and the slow-paced editing-filled with long, repetitive shots-can test the viewer's patience.\n\nIn the end, \"Secret Agent\" stands out for its strong performances and immersive atmosphere, but it's held back by its pacing and understated soundtrack.\n\nRating: 8/10."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "42c2056d-8ea6-4598-aec3-157da150fcfc", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.259955", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "67b97b3a000fbe6346809297cb3944c0e2f87c0417c78528444f22a3cc47d3c9"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "EUyeshima", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-12-19", "title": null, "content": "There's a lot going on in Brazilian director Kleber Mendon\u00e7a Filho's atmospheric 2025 political thriller set in 1977 when Brazil was under full military dictatorship and its citizens were struggling to survive through political tyranny. While there's a natural connection to be made with last year's arthouse favorite, Walter Salles' \"I'm Still Here\", Filho's film is much more complex and at select moments, chaotic and shockingly violent in a vivid Tarantino-like style. The focus is on Marcelo, who despite the film title, is not a secret agent but rather a former academic researcher who desperately needs to leave the country. His department has been shut down by a corrupt minister who sees a lucrative opportunity in transferring the research department to a private company. Marcelo's absolute resistance forces him to escape to a safe house in Recife, while the minister also sets him up for a hit. The film propels into completely unpredictable directions, which includes among several disparate elements - two separate teams of hit men, a traumatized German tailor (Udo Kier effective in his last role), and a human leg found in the jaws of a killer shark (which takes a life of its own). Playing both Marcelo and later his grown son Fernando, Wagner Moura anchors the marathon film with an impressively complex performance that earns empathy as the plot progresses. A huge cast supports deftly, in particular, T\u00e2nia Maria as Dona Sebastiana, the eccentric safe house owner, and Maria Fernanda Candida as Elza, the leader of the local resistance movement. The production values are excellent, capturing the period in great depth and with visual flair."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "50d9633d-78e5-4a86-85ff-722417e86856", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.259955", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "0c35cbe7a7c73eeb09a82e85209bd58f64ee823953a4ee4ea7264f9965a01cd9"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "NotPinpte", "rating": 8, "date": "2026-01-26", "title": null, "content": "Honestly, this movie was better than I expected. Last year, we had \"I'm Still Here\", and now, Brazil just cooked another masterpiece.\n\nThe Secret Agent is a really good movie, I just expected something else from the title, but even so, I really liked how it turned out.\n\nThere were some jokes here and there that made me laugh, and the story is pretty solid for the most part, and sometimes, I found myself nervous, not knowing what would happen next.\n\nAt times, the movie stops to focus on the main plot and just shows the characters bonding and having fun, like the whole horror leg plot, which was unexpected, but a good bit.\n\nThe ending, on the other hand, was a bit underwhelming, it does make sense and it was foreshadowing towards it, but I did expected more.\n\nBut in general, it's a really good movie, and I hope it wins \"Best International Film\"."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "54f7a880-6d39-4aea-8cd9-5deba0826c5a", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.259955", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "2eab02d83725816558463076715b491bd58d97328dc918f1107cb71b14f93364"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "binhosan", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-11-19", "title": null, "content": "Kleber Mendon\u00e7a's fifth film is sensational! With this work, he establishes himself as one of the great directors of world cinema. In this work, he addresses the tragedy of the military dictatorship in Brazil in an allegorical, acidic, raw, and often comical way. The performances are the film's strong point, with Wagner Moura giving a magnetic performance. The editing and cinematography are also strong points. It is very reminiscent of films by Tarantino and the Coen brothers. In short, it is a work to be remembered."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "00868dd5-d1b7-4abd-a55f-402d428c3100", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.260488", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "d9aa53136121da25512931b6de4aa2888b72e22b2c75baf5e9c93c29ac38528c"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "Sees All", "rating": 7, "date": "2025-12-06", "title": null, "content": "I was very excited to see this movie a few days ago because it had just won the New York Film Critics' Circle Award for both Best Picture and Best Actor. I wondered if this would have the same impact as last year's Brazilian hit, I'M STILL HERE, did. I thought it was worth seeing, but I didn't feel very passionate about it. It was set at roughly the same time as I'M STILL HERE and touched upon the same subjects, but it took its time to build any momentum. It probably would have helped if I'd had a better background in the details of the corrupt Brazilian regime of that time, but I don't. For reasons I don't fully understand, the protagonist of the story finds out that there are two hit men who have been contracted to kill him. They've already killed his wife. He has a young son who lives with his wife's parents. He worries about their safety, too. He works in technology, which moves so fast that those scenes are primitive by today's standards. There's no Internet! (Or if there is, it's so primitive that we would deem it useless today. There appears to be no search engine!) He goes undercover and uses an alias, but they continue to close in on him. There's a lot of cold-blooded violence in this movie. Every time he thinks he has eluded them, they show up again.\n\nI basically enjoyed this movie, but ultimately, I found it rather routine, despite many fine elements. It didn't really live up to the hype for me. It pales beside the great American crime thrillers of the 1970s and '80s. As for the lead performance, Wagner Moura certainly has a strong screen presence, with Latino good-looks and a natural charm. If his English is passable, he could have a big career here. The performance in this film is strongly aided by excellent makeup and hairstyling. (I have always maintained that most people confuse acting with makeup and I think this is a pretty good example.) I probably would have liked it more if I'd been expecting less."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "6d81c067-fc70-4f23-9c59-2290e461c301", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.260488", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "b3928abccc7721de547f06bd55f5b04be3807e3d736008bf4c3b97ecd48bb63f"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "RyanM-350", "rating": 8, "date": "2026-01-21", "title": null, "content": "Created with painstaking detail while divulging its narrative twists sparingly, Kleber Mendon\u00e7a Filho's The Secret Agent is a slow burn delight. By the two hour mark the audience is treated to multiple absorbing digressions and a number of delicious tracking shots.\n\nYet the exact nature of the film's plot remains elusive. By the film's conclusion multiple dangling threads remain and our natural desire for closure stymied. This goes to the film's themes of history getting lost in the fragility of memory. The modern day postscript sees the younger generation reconstructing the past as an effort to avoid historical mistakes.\n\nThe ominous and dreadful opening scene sets the tone for late 70s Brazil. The Policia Militar are more interested in harassing Wagner Moura's Marcelo (Armando) than they are in investigating a dead body in the road. The dead body can't pay a bribe.\n\nMoura established his reputation in America off the back of his towering depiction of Pablo Escobar in Narcos. It is a Television leading man performance which rivals the works of Gandolfini and Cranston. The actor offers another bravura performance in The Secret Agent, one that highlights his range. Where his Columbian drug lord is an angsty raging alpha, his research professor is an often taciturn open-hearted omega.\n\nThe Secret Agent brings to mind more recent South American history. Perhaps the hammer isn't mightier than the pen.\n\nSometimes only time will tell."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "abc19a85-9669-456e-bf0a-d20b79443552", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.260488", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "985554b6c91d20994d3defd01633ddf837644fae7dec387b85fcd0abd9119c31"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "Abyjith10", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-01-25", "title": null, "content": "Before watching this movie, I honestly think it helps to read a bit about Brazil's history. Nothing deep, just basics. That helped me a lot. Otherwise, the movie can feel confusing. It's non-linear and slightly complicated, especially if you're not familiar with Brazil's political background.\n\nThe film is slow-paced, but it's full of small details. Every scene feels loaded. It talks about corruption, colonial hangover, trauma, power, and societal decay of that period, not directly, but always in the background.\n\nThis is not a movie that ends when the credits roll. Some films are easy, you watch, you understand, finished. But this is the kind of film that stays in your head. What you understand in the first watch is actually very little. When you think about it again and again, more meanings start opening up. A rewatch will definitely reveal a lot of symbolism and hidden details.\n\nThe ending might feel frustrating at first because there is no proper closure. You'll even question the director. But that's the point. The real incidents this film reflects never got closure, and that unresolved trauma is exactly what the film makes us feel. Once that clicks, the ending makes sense.\n\nYes, at times it feels laggy, but the mystery keeps you going. In the third act, once violence enters, the film becomes more intense and gripping.\n\nThe movie is completely about corruption, internal, external, political, societal, everywhere. Even small dialogues and background details are filled with it. That's when you realise this is not just Brazil's story. Corruption exists everywhere.\n\nIt also shows a harsh truth: justice is expensive. Justice mostly belongs to those who can afford it.\n\nBecause of all these layers and detailing, the Oscar nomination makes complete sense. This is not simple cinema, it's cinema that asks you to think.\n\nOverall, a good watch. Not for everyone, but if it works for you, it really stays with you."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "ee299cba-643f-483c-84ec-b9760a155f74", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.260488", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "d8a9a04e62db639e5406c3c4d75c6f296acf34f62925243ed405230e34f7c02b"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "ProfWinerReviews", "rating": 8, "date": "2026-01-14", "title": null, "content": "If you liked him as Pablo Escobar in Narcos and in Civil War, you will love Wagner Moura in this film. Although the movie runs long (2:41) and the story can get a little confusing, the end result is more than satisfying. Directed and written by Brazilian Kleber Mendon\u00e7a Filho, the film takes the craziness of 1977 Brazil under a dictatorship, a story around a man trying to change his identity, and a large and talented cast (see in particular T\u00e2nia Maria as Dona Sebastiana) to make a film that I enjoyed from beginning to end.\n\nMoura plays a high-tech expert who is trying to evade his past by changing his name from Marcelo to Armando and moving to Recife during Carnival. His wife has died and his son Fernando lives with the maternal grandparents. Armando lives in a house run by Dona Sebastiana with other political refugees. He is trying to escape his past by taking a position in a local government records office. In a subplot that is not fully explained, he spends some of his time in the records office searching for lost identity records of his mother. Unfortunately, he cannot escape his past and he is targeted for assassination by a corrupt business executive who has a grudge against Marcelo/Armando. He is urged to flee the country while violence erupts among the local police and the hit men. The film ends with an update: Fernando is now a doctor in Recife but does not remember his father despite the availability of audio recordings and newspaper accounts.\n\nThe above plot does not adequately describe Filho's wonderful storytelling that kept me spellbound for the entire movie. There is Moura's acting, the great cast full of colorful people, the setting of 1970s Brazil, and humor largely based around a shark (I won't give it away). This is definitely worth seeing."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "85771c0f-48e7-4f9e-a117-5726c875b167", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.260488", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "5abe698171aba3c7544d2ddbc35c1710b06b9b6be2955f6463c78ae16fbacd58"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "alain_pinel", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-01-17", "title": null, "content": "A perfect 70s aesthetic, evident in the costumes, hairstyles, and sets, as well as the film grain and camera angles. The lengthy setup of the plot requires some patience, but the script's reward is well worth the effort. Wagner Moura is indeed excellent. A beautiful way to conclude the film. To be savored with patience."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "bd12b591-0a4e-49a5-8f02-e8e0e751216e", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.260488", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "f3b7ad8f447797219eff95183c4ba9f4a40dd2920093ab2bdfed0c5128f31e53"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "prietoanamaria", "rating": 4, "date": "2025-11-30", "title": null, "content": "I don'tunderstand the hype with this movie, it must be just a nationalistic one, or because Moura is the main character,but this is one of the worst movies I've seen in a long time. Great production and great actors, but what a terrible screenplay. After one hour (!!!) you still don't know what the film is about, what the conflict is. More than half of the it does not bring anything to the story and are just random scenes, with interesting characters and great cinematography, yes, but leading nowhere. I saw it in the cinema and it really felt like a lost of time and money."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "be195a56-eb17-4280-874f-1f030499b1c3", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.260488", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "fc6a19eee8ce49e88dee8f68d54739fa22f8e40924fd58e244032ff61f50279f"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "dromasca", "rating": 9, "date": "2026-01-19", "title": null, "content": "There is no espionage story in 'O agente secreto' ('The Secret Agent') by Brazilian director Kleber Mendon\u00e7a Filho, nor is there any connection to the novel written by James Conrad more than a century ago, which inspired many other films and television series. It is one of those films that is difficult to fit into a single cinematic style, which can belong to several genres or for which a special category should be invented. The film borrows its title from a scene in which the main character passes through a cinema hall in which the credits of a film (imaginary, with Belmondo!) of that name are being projected. 'O agente secreto' is also full of references to cinema around 1977 and in particular to Steven Spielberg's 1975 blockbuster 'Jaws' - and a screening room is the setting for several key scenes. This complex and interesting movie does not belong to the genre of films about films either. It combines political realism with Latin American fantastic to depict the struggle for survival of people living in a corrupt and violent society, in the midst of a period of dictatorship that lasted many decades and dominated the history of Brazil in the second half of the 20th century.\n\nThe film starts as a road movie in the semi-desert landscape of northern Brazil, an arid country strewn with corpses and dominated by fear, to evolve into an atypical political thriller with a slow movie pace. The main hero is called Marcello or maybe Armando, as he sometimes hides his real identity. He flees from the authorities and the hired killers sent on his trail, waiting for the false passports that will allow him and his little boy to leave the country. The city of Recife where he arrives is a place of refuge and perhaps of transit to freedom or, in any case, to a world where his life is not in danger. A corner of a country dominated by political terror and endemic corruption. The reasons for his behavior will be gradually discovered by the viewers who will also get to know those around him: his deceased wife's parents, his neighbors - most of whom are fugitives like him -, the gullible politicians, the corrupt policemen and the hired killers, a kind of Tarantino-style heroes transported to Brazilian soil. Flashbacks will gradually complete the story of the film's hero's life, and the events that rush towards the end will only be clarified and put into context by an epilogue that takes place in our days.\n\nI also really liked the way the screenwriter and director Kleber Mendon\u00e7a Filho built the narrative and how he brought it to the screen, transforming the cinematic spectacle into a violent realistic image of Brazil in the eighth decade of the last century. Mixed in are also elements of fantasy, as present in many novels and films of Latin America, which are packaged in this case with elements of Hollywood cinematic mythology. Spielberg and (again) Tarantino seem to have met in an episode of men under a history of dictatorship, fear and repression. I appreciated the remarkable gallery of portraits created by the filmmaker and exceptionally interpreted by a collection of formidable selected and guided actors. I will mention only two names: that of Wagner Moura who has already collected well-deserved awards for the lead role in the film and the German actor Udo Kier, in his last appearance on the screens in a heartbreaking supporting role. The full list should be very long. In my opinion, in this year with serious competition, 'O agente secreto' should collect several Academy Awards, and not just the one for Best Film in a Foreign Language."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "eefb47d0-72c7-4e08-bb4f-1de4d8e0d183", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.260488", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "761cb2f64ea68fc41901b63532210be4b68b99f09ea8ee5cb411ccf7ced76761"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "matheusdavi-01446", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-12-18", "title": null, "content": "The Secret Agent delivers a solid narrative supported by strong performances and well-chosen cast. The film builds multiple layers of dramatic depth, with Wagner Moura standing out in a consistently compelling lead role. However, its excessive runtime at times slows the pace, and the final sequence feels less impactful."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "a45d8f0d-c780-48c6-96ca-272a16e0b031", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.260488", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "7ea4b4b0de77b92bed6a60607e4e1c085bbe4394b279774511e0c4a4b4999f87"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "felipearielm", "rating": 9, "date": "2025-12-29", "title": null, "content": "The film has a very interesting and beautiful representation of Brazil in the 70s, full of cool references to the culture of the time, including films from the 70s that are now classic cults. The pacing builds up to a strong ending, that i have to admit i felt it was interrupted. The final persecution scene left everyone in the theater on the edge of their sits, but for some reason the director cuts for another scene and ends the film... but overall quite good film, it impresses me how brazilian cinema is evolving fast, one film better than the other, lately. The Secret Agent is not the action thriller in the \"Hollywood\" sense, because it has a lot of political undertones and works with cultural peculiarities from southern american countries that western cinema has dificulty to understand and value, but it's quite a unique film from a national industry that is learning how to make films using the aesthetics and comercial language from Hollywood, and it's working quite well."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "7bd7ac08-47de-4e6a-a4b9-d02e3d131ad4", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.260488", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "fa03e986d829c9d428e9e1b9a2b16d226a9f8acc8549c000324a13b81f5111da"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "augustovlucca", "rating": 8, "date": "2026-01-13", "title": null, "content": "This one takes its time and doesn't rush anything. It's very talky, very slow, but in a way that feels intentional. The tension isn't about big moments, it's more about the constant unease, like something bad is always just around the corner.\n\nThe mood does a lot of the work here. Everything feels heavy, suspicious, and morally messy, and that's what makes it interesting. On top of that, the art direction is excellent, with a strong visual identity and carefully composed frames that give the film a distinct look and atmosphere.\n\nQuiet, smart, and surprisingly gripping once it clicks."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "2b6a10e2-50ae-48c2-8ad4-13725da5cd72", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.260488", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "5f002d063a1e08b90d2a72c93b8b9709f0d78c2a9948a4ad80d89f01748900a4"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "lyoneduardo", "rating": 6, "date": "2026-01-26", "title": null, "content": "\"The Secret Agent\" is Brazil's latest nomination for the Oscar's International Feature category. Filled with Brazilian northeastern 'ginga', the somewhat weird film has been claiming important awards ever since its 2025 Cannes debut. The main plot follows Marcelo, an on-the-run former teacher and tech expert that flies back to Recife - PE, where he will soon find out he is still in danger.\n\nWagner Moura's portrayal is amazing and deserving of the worldwide acclaim he is receiving (even earned the 2026 Golden Globe for Best Actor). Filled with many non-actors, the splendid casting is also nominated for this new Academy Award category, and I must mention some of my favorite depictions: Dona Sebastiana, deputy Euclides and the gas station attendant. The cinematography and the production design deserve reverence as well. A perfect recreation of the city of Recife circa 1977, praised as accurate and very pretty to watch.\n\nThe story mixes reality with local folklore references and even Roman mythology (Janus cat) whenever possible. Most of what is seen has no explanation or motive and the audience is left with many loose ends. Nonetheless, a few themes are constantly present, some with repetition. Did you notice death, blood, shark throughout the film? And the lack of explanation, would that be like real life, where so much happens without a noticeable reason or aim?\n\nIt seems the director Kleber Mendon\u00e7a Filho wanted to make the audience think about what was left unsaid, while showing us the cheap side of humanity, selling itself for money, corruption and power on all levels of society. Not much has changed since 1977, or ever mankind came to exist."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "ee0a3997-8b78-41c1-a2dc-55a2b8580f4a", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.261003", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "66dd0eb4afd2c2808bca0c6da3210c19f39befbffeb02d183b7b9c46261b2d6b"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "cdriclria-33737", "rating": 9, "date": "2025-12-17", "title": null, "content": "When i saw this movie, the first thing which came in my mind was : \"the World is so tiny\" !... Every people you meet each day, can be your Best Friend or your Worst Enemy. Ours lives depend on the WHEEL of FORTUNE, it was written, this is the Fate !... This picture was awarded \"Best Director\" & \"Best Actor\" to the last Cannes Film Festival... in my opinion, the best actor prize was accurate, but i question the best director award ?!... I would give it, the best screenplay instead. Wagner Moura's portrayal was fine, i really hope his name will be called on January 22, 2026 in the Best Actor Category, for the next Academy Award Season. When you watched the whole movie, you understand, this is a Family movie on several generations. I really love the film, in a certain way all movies which talk about Brazil, care for me, (Central Station, I'm Still Here, etc...) This was a very good experience watching it, i hope people will love it too."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "767bbab5-8bea-4edc-8b88-8f2aedfa0bed", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.261003", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "a951d6dadc46134cb86e590ccd7196f86315c80d372f76e005959b358cedae43"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "sami2005", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-01-26", "title": null, "content": "The Secret Agent is an engaging and visually appealing film that explores corruption and how powerful individuals can damage their own countries for personal gain. Its message about moral decay and abuse of power feels relevant and thought-provoking, giving the story meaningful weight. The atmosphere is enhanced by a beautiful and well-chosen musical score that complements the film's tone and emotional moments.\n\nHowever, while the concept and direction are strong, some performances fall short of their potential. Not all actors deliver the same level of intensity or depth, which slightly weakens the overall impact. Despite these flaws, The Secret Agent remains a solid and worthwhile watch, driven by its themes, mood, and striking presentation."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "420d5b6a-f89c-43b5-a0b4-c1a74ec37508", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.261003", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "a77bfdf57cb93817c782dcd7719c340e7073b0bf9987ac1cc755023f2b28a5d0"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "lusobrosa", "rating": 9, "date": "2026-01-04", "title": null, "content": "The Secret Agent finds its greatest brilliance in the way it closes its own narrative. By revealing Armando/Marcelo's death through a newspaper, the film does something rare and profoundly human: it shows that life simply goes on. The son, who loved his father deeply, grows up - and because he lost him so early, barely remembers him as an adult. As happens with so many real lives.\n\nThere is something harsh and deeply true in this. Our lives matter immensely while we are living them, yet many of them are lost in the vast sea of time and space. And when they do survive, they are not always remembered as they truly were. We do not control our own narrative - and the film seems painfully aware of this silent tragedy.\n\nThat said, the film's pacing is debatable. The plot unfolds with great artistry and restraint, supported by exceptional production design. The faded tones of the 1970s are not merely aesthetic; they feel like a state of mind. The production is impeccable in every detail.\n\nWagner Moura's performance is outstanding. At many moments, I completely forgot the actor and truly believed I was watching Marcelo/Armando himself. That kind of disappearance of the actor into the character is rare and powerful.\n\nBy the end, I was deeply impressed - but I would not watch it again. This is not a film made for entertainment. It is intense, dense, almost emotionally exhausting. There is something cathartic about it, and perhaps even nihilistic, in the sense that it confronts the loss of meaning, the erosion of memory, and the indifference of time toward individual stories.\n\nThe Secret Agent does not comfort. It confronts. And perhaps that is precisely why it leaves such a lasting impact."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "ad245804-b2b3-4ab5-9a64-9b620df4d248", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.261003", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "889530c43577304e1424e7ff87cffa02fe66dde414af5d4fba45392114cbbe3e"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "rickchatenever", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-01-24", "title": null, "content": "If you're not fond of the sight of blood, you might think twice about seeing \"The Secret Agent.\" Blood is the glue trying together the chapters of this Brazilian political thriller just nominated for four Academy Awards after winning the best-actor Golden Globe for Wagner Moura.\n\nBlood is both symbol and metaphor ... not to mention literal, as gallons of the stuff flows through the fast-paced action. It comes from numerous donors, including one gnarly shark. Sharks, and the movie \"Jaws,\" are another recurrent theme for writer-director Kleber Mendonca Filho.\n\nMarcelo Alves (Moura) is not a secret agent. Instead, he is a one-time university professor forced underground by Brazil's military dictatorship of the 1970s after defying a ruthless industrialist trying to appropriate one of his patents.\n\nNow Marcelo is living in limbo in the city of Recife at carnaval time, hiding under an assumed identity in a halfway house for leftist enemies of the state, awaiting forged documents so he and his young son can flea the country.\n\nSo rather than a badge of James Bond-style prowess, \"Secret Agent\" is, instead, a label bestowed on him by the authoritarian regime. A label, like illegal alien. Or domestic terrorist. Or a very nasty person ... Filmmaker Filho paints the screen with washed-out primary colors and other details of '70s culture. Marcelo (that's no longer his name) drives a rickety yellow VW bug through streets teeming with revelers in front of gaudy storefronts. The line blurs between mardi gras hedonism and the frightened vigilance and other sorts of paranoia pervading life 24/7.\n\nBullying oppression goes hand-in-hand with wall-to-wall corruption. The hired hitmen on Marcelo's trail are in cahoots with - or no different from - the father-and-sons goons running the police force. The journalists entrusted with reporting \"the news\" have to resort to coded urban legends like \"the hairy leg,\" a disembodied appendage that attacks LGBT+ lovers in public parks, rather than reporting the actual police brutality that leaves its victims in hospitals and morgues.\n\nMoura's performance spans the broadest range of emotions, from loving father and husband to an Everyman caught in a Kafkaesque political nightmare. Writer-director Filho has also received his share of awards beginning at Cannes, not just for the detail of this period piece, but for viscerally sharing the pit-of-the-stomach terror of living under an authoritarian dictatorship.\n\nAudiences elsewhere in the world, like those in his native Brazil, are familiar with the feeling.\n\nIn the U. S., it's still a new sensation."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "bb991d18-52a5-49f3-b4de-cb3c59b44045", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.261003", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "0a84728012d882ac99a50b276df472f03a2592c0290900dfaa15073da2cb9b0c"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "brentsbulletinboard", "rating": 4, "date": "2025-10-19", "title": null, "content": "The key to making a successful political thriller is to maintain a taught sense of mesmerizing, edge-of-the-seat intrigue. Unfortunately, that's precisely the element that's missing in this overlong, annoyingly convoluted tale set in 1977 Brazil during the waning days of its military dictatorship. The story follows the life of Armando (Wagner Moura), a former university researcher targeted for manipulation and framing by a corrupt, influential businessman (Luciano Chirolli) when the educator refuses to play ball with him. This, in turn, leads to a death threat against Armando, who must do whatever it takes to try and clear his name and stay alive. In the process, however, Armando gets caught up in a web of deceit, criminality and personal peril involving a shady police chief and his dubious associates, a pair of ruthless hitmen, a group of Brazilian and Angolan political dissidents in hiding, and a Holocaust survivor mistakenly believed to be a Nazi refugee. From this, it would appear that the film has a premise filled with potential to make for an engaging yarn, but, regrettably, it fails under the weight of its many shortcomings, most notably an overextended narrative that excessively delves into the details of government research funding and sociopolitical clashes involving regional Brazilian cultural and political differences, material that's often tedious and not especially engaging. To complicate matters, director Kleber Mendon\u00e7a Filho has compiled a mishmash of filming and storytelling styles that frequently impairs the picture's flow and style, including a wealth of easily excised incidental material that tries viewer patience the further one gets into the story. This is clearly a case of a filmmaker in need of reining himself in, knowing when to kill his darlings, and unsuccessfully maintaining a level of suspense that, sadly, largely evaporates about an hour into the picture. In addition, this offering incorporates a present-day story thread involving a history student (Laura Luf\u00e9si) assigned to transcribe surveillance tape recordings of Armando made at the height of his ordeal, a task that inexplicably captivates her, prompting her to learn more about the fate of her subject. It's a needless subplot that evokes a huge \"so what?\" quality and could have readily been eliminated without damaging the picture in the slightest. I'm truly mystified how this bloated release ended up being the most honored candidate at this year's Cannes Film Festival, capturing four awards, including best actor and director, as well as a Palme d'Or nomination, the event's highest honor. This is a genre with so many other better offerings that one would be wise to watch in place of this disappointing effort."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "fe4918b6-fc2d-4687-a30d-15e6620bf043", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.261003", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "c30aaceb229ad87a71c10d5a250b989543848791a5bf4faa621eeadd60e35e7c"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "rhuamaaz", "rating": 10, "date": "2025-12-25", "title": null, "content": "What fascinated me most about The Secret Agent is how the film operates through silence, implication, and tension rather than exposition. Its political dimension is always present, but never didactic. Power, surveillance, fear, and masculinity are explored through gestures, absences, and atmosphere instead of speeches. The film trusts the viewer to read between the lines - and that trust is rare and deeply satisfying.\n\nThere is also a strong sense of Recife as both myth and territory. The city is not just a backdrop, but a living presence shaped by memory, folklore, and urban tension. The film's connection to street-level cinema - grounded, physical, and attentive to everyday spaces - reinforces its political and symbolic weight. Restrained, unsettling, and deeply intelligent, this is an 10/10."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "72ea3847-81e5-4d8e-91ed-2377e1159b88", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.261003", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "1e8c4fb599de616c36375c4d7ba6ce6d71b3775ced8f53962b4a28799ad8de51"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "jjr4", "rating": 8, "date": "2026-01-04", "title": null, "content": "Brazil in the 1970s, military regime is brutal, and ultra-liberal economy feeds, as in other dictatorships, a rampant omnipresent corruption amongst the powerful, the uniformed and, basically, anyone who has information or a neighbour to sell.\n\nKleber Mendon\u00e7a Filho, the director and writer, has a taste for the resistance and resilience of ordinary people against institutionalised violence. His central characters, each of them brilliantly brought to the screen by an inspired cast, is un-ambiguous morally but ethically confused. From corrupt policemen and their lot to fleeing idealist and his network of helpers, they belong to a manichaeans world split, but their actions tend to get away from them and the side they incarnate. That prevents the 160 minutes length of the film to become boring.\n\nThat, plus the beautiful cinematography. Colour becomes a language of itself, which often emphasises by opposition the darkness of the actions. For instance the drab repulsive corruption of day to day policemen is even more blatant when shot in a dried out extra sunny landscape of fields, by the whitewashed walls and roadsigns of a gas station, where a Yellow Volkswagen driver is their target feet away from a days old decaying body, which everybody ignores but a hoard of famished dogs.\n\nBeyond being a tense thriller, the movie is also a political work. Two movies are quoted, The Omen, and Jaws, two perfect caricatures of evil lurking below the surface of the United States colonial and eco-liberal politics of the sixties and seventies, often relying on authoritarian conservative regimes installation. Mendon\u00e7a Filho may well be delivering us a warning as to the return of these times. Similarly, the suggestion that carnivals and/or sensationalist tabloid like medias participate in hiding from us deeper violence and oppression is probably not a gratuitous twist of the scenario. But this is done discreetly and does not distract from the core thriller genre of the movie: Individual running away from a corrupt network of powerful enemies and trying to save himself and his family."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "16299cfb-0c85-449f-81c1-1c98819c5b2e", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.261003", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "34c3aee1d6116a2d175c115e642fc5c7c0936709ba36e12dd059c2b471e1ff2f"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "teharatats", "rating": 9, "date": "2025-12-22", "title": null, "content": "Catching my breath first - an incredible piece of art. Notes of Pulp Fiction, Z, Kiss Of The Spider-woman here. With the US President a big wonderful fan of imprisoned Bolsonaro, it is a gut-punch as friends and lovers are tested on commitment to freedom and the rule of law. Succeed. Fail. Try to forget.\n\nThis is a beautiful gripping case study on the runaway corruption that has seeded the morally flexible authoritarian mileu we're up to today. Definitely an award worthy and morally worthy piece."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "b5c875f5-4ee2-4723-b870-0a289218ea40", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.261003", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "eba46187e19dec345d9125694c0d66ce00c4a9b38dfa9f035047c177308e952e"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "steiner-sam", "rating": 9, "date": "2025-12-13", "title": null, "content": "It's a political drama set in 1977, with flashbacks to 1974, in Racife, Brazil, during the Brazilian military dictatorship. The film's conclusion takes place 25 years later. Armando (Wagner Moura), a former university researcher, arrives back in Racife in 1977, a semi-fugitive hoping to emigrate to a university position outside the country. He was cheated by a powerful businessman, Salvatore Ghirotti (Gregorio Graziosi), with links to the military leadership. Armando goes to a \"refugee\" center hosted by 77-year-old Dona Sebastiana (T\u00e2nia Maria). Others, including Elza (Maria Fernanda C\u00e2ndido). Meanwhile, Ghirotti arranges with two hitmen (Roney Villela and Gabriel Leone) to find and eliminate Armando. They, in turn, hire a local, Vilmar (Kaiony Ven\u00e2ncio), to carry out the task for a pittance. Many complications arise.\n\n\"O Agente Secreto\" is a truly fascinating film. The storyline is creative, and the characters are all off-center just enough to remain intriguing throughout the story. In addition to those mentioned above, they include the corrupt police chief, Euclides (Rob\u00e9rio Di\u00f3genes), the upstairs neighbor, Claudia (Hermila Guedes), and Armando's father-in-law, Alexandre (Carlos Francisco). However, \"O Agente Secreto\" is disjointed enough to keep it from being a great film. A quirky opening sequence and a missing leg help set the tone for this creative effort. The ending returns us to reality. Wagner Moura turns in a top-flight performance.\n\nI've since watched it a second time and changed my rating from 8 to 9. I understood many more of the plot hints distributed throughout, impressing me even more."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "721d2147-27f9-4dfc-8893-40075798c8fc", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.261003", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "8b0ba1279f7034ac7cc8b9db16c93c381c99f9e2050dc6f78b6a685e49a841af"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "rodrigopirmez", "rating": 10, "date": "2025-12-22", "title": null, "content": "I had read some mixed critical comments about the film, but it is a masterpiece.\n\nWhile some characters are slightly exaggerated for effect, the performances are striking. Certain scenes are somewhat absurd, yet the film never feels completely disconnected from reality. It portrays the harsh and violent period Brazil was going through in a somewhat \"lighter\" way, using subtle motifs to remind us that these were years of dictatorship.\n\nPure Oscar material!"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "7d88d5a7-83e1-41da-9b8d-b5ed5ec30a4a", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.261003", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "e4825e5a32d94d5900213d28f51da6afeec1a23f77bf34ea73859c862513f2b5"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "JooP-8237", "rating": 8, "date": "2026-01-26", "title": null, "content": "Wagner Moura, as always, embodies his characters and deserves to win an Oscar. The film's plot highlights a very dark period in Brazilian history without providing a direct historical deep dive. It portrays scars that we still carry today, such as corruption, the malfunctioning of the public administration, and impunity. Unlike I'm Still Here, which directly delves into the subject and the government's direct persecution, this film shows that there is no way to confront those who have the machinery of the state on their side."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "41f7f209-6cb7-4484-ae81-2e2510f20522", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.261003", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "4f79da69eee34e34506a76f9f506bed834b6d25d1cdd22f9323af76353f20200"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "alexandrenpes", "rating": 4, "date": "2025-11-08", "title": null, "content": "I think you'll hate unless you are from Pernambuco. Then you might like. Might.\n\nStory is too long and nothing happens. Things are lost and disconnected.\n\nI really don't understand the hype in some movies. It seems that people say they like just because everybody else is doing the same. I'd recommend you to not watch."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "7145211c-478d-4b24-951f-6e1e90430533", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.261003", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "6e4a31125202e5934092128db875028d64d0f6b54d24e7d53fa3f3981266a769"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "FOIVOSN", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-12-16", "title": null, "content": "There are many political comment in this movie like the communist granny, the couple from Angola, etc? It is so rich in political and social commentary. But i would say that it is an esay political commentary in relation to other films like \"O som ao redor'', or Aquarius'' or even Bacurau that plays with stereotypes.\n\nNowadays the popular and historical center of the city of Recife is under renovation and gentrification processes that are changing the mix of the population. How does this film inscribes in the actual political processes in Recife? It is clear that there a critical stance on the dictatorship but in relation to what is happening in Recife it does not take poisition like ''O som ao redor\" and ''Aquarius\". It is more of a middle class nostalgia of an epoch that ended. This is exactly the sentiment of many people that is being instrumentalized by the current city administration to gentrify the historical areas of Recife, the areas that are seen in the movie. I think that this time Kleber choose to not make an actual critic into what is happening in the city. That's why his film is easily promoted everywhere . It is easier to use it for leftist memorabilia touristification projects, than to actual make a serious political argument. There is an contradiction between ''O som ao redor'' and ''Acquarius\"' during more difficult political moments, and now."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "6e6eb503-6c6a-477f-bea4-720f44982da0", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.261003", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "af0851cf3721dcf989d57dde3935ef3e6b270fc57463fcac6a8089e888649bfb"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "otelorigato", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-12-22", "title": null, "content": "The film is an authentic portrayal of the violent and corrupt Brazilian dictatorship, and sensitively shows the contrast between the barbarity and uncivilized behavior of the police and the economic elite with the friendly and kind nature of the people from the Brazilian Northeast, in this case represented by Pernambuco, Mendon\u00e7a-Filho's home state. It's worth highlighting the perfect recreation of an era and the impeccable work of the main actors, especially Wagner Moura, an actor as talented as he is charismatic. Perhaps the ending is a little frustrating for a film with such a breakneck pace, but nothing is perfect."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "a89efa38-491d-452e-9e39-cd6cca1d774e", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.261003", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "0e7a208e2f188f35d742fbd54a6243a8615374b4ba1cce4fff0cbac3fb1cd5de"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "CarlosMCabrero", "rating": 10, "date": "2026-01-24", "title": null, "content": "I had a great time with this movie, it gave me a great insight about Brazil during that period that I find really interesting. Somehow it's keeps you hooked to the trama. The acting was great. I understand now why is nominated, it is really good. Waner has become one of my favorite actors, he is very versatile, carries the whole movie on his shoulders, which I find outstanding."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "fe22c773-0584-45c5-baf2-0d537646fa73", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.261003", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "4eaed5f961aa73446b9a05404f8789d44a3855d06d3aed7d912374bfc7c76f38"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "LuanMarques1992", "rating": 5, "date": "2026-01-22", "title": null, "content": "The Brazilian film industry is living through an almost unprecedented moment of recognition, both at home and abroad. For years, the idea persisted that Brazil did not know how to make cinema, as if our production were limited to empty comedies from Rede Globo. Today, we are finally beginning to look at our own cinema with more maturity. The problem starts when recognition automatically becomes a synonym for quality. That is exactly where The Secret Agent enters the discussion.\n\nI came in with high expectations. I did not watch it in a movie theater, but the weight of Cannes, the Critics Choice Awards, and the Golden Globes had already created a promise of greatness. The shock was immediate: international praise does not guarantee personal involvement. What is acclaimed does not always connect with the viewer.\n\nI love historical productions, especially when major periods are shown through the eyes of those who are not at the center of power. That was how I saw The Secret Agent: the chance to follow an ordinary civilian being crushed by the dictatorship. Something very different from I'm Still Here (2024), which follows Rubens Paiva, a politician, a man from the social and intellectual elite. Here, the promise was different. The problem is that it is never fulfilled.\n\nThe main obstacle is the screenplay: bloated, exhausting, and without a clear direction. There are too many unnecessary scenes and a constant sense of dispersion. It takes two hours and forty minutes for the film to finally try, only at the end, to say clearly what it actually wants to be.\n\nThe much-talked-about \"hairy leg\" is the symbol of this detour. The Northeastern legend appears in a scene that is completely out of place, extremely stupid, and dramatically useless. It deepens nothing, expands no theme, and contributes nothing to the narrative. It only interrupts the rhythm and provokes the inevitable question: what am I watching?\n\nIf it lost an hour of runtime, went through a new edit, and focused more on Marcelo's escape and his motivations, the film would be infinitely better. It lacks synthesis and suffers from indulgence.\n\nStill, there are clear merits. Wagner Moura delivers an impeccable performance. T\u00e2nia Maria is the great revelation, with a magnetic screen presence. The recreation of the 1970s is excellent: costumes, sets, cinematography, and aesthetic references are all carefully crafted. Technically, it is a rich and meticulous work.\n\nBut cinema, above all, is screenplay. And this screenplay is fragile. When it fails, everything else becomes ornament. It can be beautiful, sophisticated, and well-produced, but it is never enough to compensate for the lack of narrative strength.\n\nI watched it on the eve of the Oscar nominations and, like any good Brazilian, I still hope it gets nominated. International recognition carries symbolic weight. It is just tiring to pretend that awards are synonymous with quality. They are, first and foremost, politics.\n\nThe Secret Agent rides on the impact created by Walter Salles's film. Both deal with the dictatorship, but the similarities end there. While one is striking and revolutionary, the other is diffuse and easily forgettable. One establishes itself as a reference work. The other sounds like a footnote.\n\nIt hurts to write this, because I wanted to like it. But The Secret Agent does not seem strong enough to survive the test of time in the popular imagination."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "f1b915a0-7455-4e0f-a74f-569978f54c0d", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.261003", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "2e065b9f7a36fe919dbfc5ab68499bcc334419d8d2b4d12b5477bcddb9ffc375"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "vhpcampos", "rating": 1, "date": "2026-01-15", "title": null, "content": "While the espionage genre usually promises high-stakes tension and pulse-pounding intrigue, The Secret Agent delivers all the excitement of watching a committee file paperwork. Instead of a sharp, cinematic thriller, audiences are served a sluggish, heavy-handed narrative that feels less like art and more like a taxpayer-funded lecture."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "fc56de94-ec85-4e74-94e0-2af0cd5232d5", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.261003", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "48edf896379d1777295e1d57ad7e98fabcca981f519748bab4eb66099d5bde6a"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "thomasvconti", "rating": 1, "date": "2025-11-24", "title": null, "content": "O Agente Secreto contains many of the ingredients of a great film - most notably its striking cinematography - but ultimately collapses into a frustrating, self-sabotaging mess.\n\nWagner Moura delivers his customary strong performance, yet his character is a vacuum: dull, passive, and inexplicably foolish. He is being hunted, knows he needs only to remain hidden for four days before leaving the country with his son, and nonetheless repeatedly endangers himself - and others - because of... an obsessive quest to recover his dead mother's ID card?\n\nThe film offers no rationale for this fixation, no psychological grounding, only a series of plot-driven acts of idiocy. There is no real urgency, only plot convenience.\n\nNo other character fares better. Figures drift in, perform whatever function the plot requires, and vanish without development or consequence. The film leans heavily on familiar Latin American political clich\u00e9s - the unrecognized intellectual, folkloric mysticism as metaphor, sadistic military officers, willfully \"poetic\" ambiguity - yet never earns their presence or explores them with any depth.\n\nBy the time it reaches its cold, shrug-of-the-shoulders non-ending, the result is 160 minutes of exquisite images wrapped around nothing at all. Pretentious, empty, and smugly self-satisfied, the film is especially infuriating because of the vast gap between its potential and its long, meager delivery."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "3edf8b69-d7bb-4e76-9933-0fd541005288", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.261003", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "a59fb1799558892e99183a6d2c648cbdc5d99eb352f3996704ecbfa8b5f8ff0f"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "SoumikBanerjee1996", "rating": 4, "date": "2026-01-20", "title": null, "content": "Aside from the captivating opening sequence and a somewhat engaging climax, I find that the film falls short of achieving its intended objectives, whether as a political critique or a thrilling narrative.\n\nInstead, it seems to linger in an 'in-between' space that feels distant and elusive, making it hard for me to appreciate its qualities or maintain my interest throughout its duration, if truth be told, it just didn't hold my attention.\n\nWagner Moura's portrayal of Armando is commendable; he infuses the character with warmth and authenticity.\n\nHowever, considering the backdrop of the story, i.e. Brazil under a military dictatorship in '77, I anticipated a far more impactful and profound exploration of the subject matter in hand.\n\nI can still vividly remember Walter Salles' 'I'm Still Here,' which had garnered accolades at the Academy Awards previously, which In my humble opinion, was a much superior film that not only made the core characters feel close to me but also intricately wove comparable themes about dictatorship, murders, societal anarchy etc."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "17d16091-e561-4520-be64-fcfad7270ae0", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.261859", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "9a3b9fba10522def363990ccafe81ceeda28f0e2cb38202a5ae6aafa94f66cf5"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "morningbugle-60910", "rating": 1, "date": "2025-12-03", "title": null, "content": "Yes I am pampered by all the abundance of various movies, yes my span of attention is low and getting lower. But, man, was this a boring, boring movie.\n\nI went to see it in cinema and was not able to leave the cinema. Every minute seemed like a century... Yes, I do not speak Portugese and I do not know the Brasilian culture and history, maybe I missed something, but the story is boring, difficult to understand, without logic... If they had cut it to 90 minutes it would have been equally shallow and uninteresting, but at least the terror would have lasted some 70 minutes less, and every minute counts with this masterpiece of movie boredom."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "fe10c709-b8d2-405b-84f0-4f68c409cd5b", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.261859", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "e7055465de629a66bbfed6b184f8f8b530871790b2e7b88f686ae30573015b48"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "deleyshaun", "rating": 3, "date": "2026-01-25", "title": null, "content": "The Secret Agent is premised on a professor ( Moura) in hiding due to reasons that surface later in the film. This gives the director plenty of scope to flesh out the day to day corruption, secrecy, disregard of life, and general living conditions of the 1970s military rule of Brazil. This is done with excellent cinematography and a plethora of characters and dialogue. Where the film fails is its inability to hook the audience into being invested or caring. A lot of the scenes were mundane , lacking coherency , intensity and engrossment. It masquerades as a thriller but lacks thrills- it's more a social commentary of the time. Perhaps a better understanding of Brazilian life and subculture would have helped but the director is appealing to an international audience so no excuse here.( many foreign films have an unfamiliar culture portrayed to the audience much more successfully ). The acting is good, and it feels very realistic thanks to the cinematography. A reasonable third act with a fair resolution cannot save this disappointment. Give it a miss. It will not win best film despite its surprise nomination."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "6ba1cae0-f2be-4363-8f76-c1ec4262992c", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.261859", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "d23bbb5f34b531a1b4e9cf59667b589ab5efc0a19df30c0b49290b9527be2cdb"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "josetron", "rating": 4, "date": "2026-01-24", "title": null, "content": "As usual, these \"weird\" movies find their way to the Oscars \ud83d\ude02. The Night Agent has a painfully slow pace, and for long stretches you feel like you're watching clues without a map. The atmosphere and production are solid, and there are moments that look genuinely well made, but the script feels messy and underwritten. Instead of building tension, it drifts, repeats itself, and leaves key beats unclear-so the payoff doesn't hit the way it should. With a tighter edit and a clearer narrative spine, this could've been a really strong film. As it is, it's more frustrating than intriguing."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "95b0a644-ddf7-4bcd-9dc4-ef840bb6c3b2", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.261859", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "456ad83395318f90ff48b0a28f12142f26e48f999c094e6ba28ecb2a62bc8f94"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "Stargrazingreviews", "rating": 5, "date": "2026-01-23", "title": null, "content": "I headed into this really looking forward to it but was quickly met by the realisation that this was not well catered to the uninitiated, given that without any knowledge of 1970s Brazilian politics, I was missing out on key plot details and character motivations. The failure to convey necessary context is a valid criticism, considering that the film is catering to an international audience. The plot moves glacially for the first two hours, and despite being stylishly shot, I did not find it engaging and was prepared to give an more negative review. However, the final act is more tense, action-packed and intriguing thematically, so it ended on a strong point."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "57cdd1b9-d40f-4bb1-8491-437f8b1bd4b2", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.261859", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "b9ac187471fe0befcb457c576d594641235a6b6d5cb0e62f73d39d1bf5569a2c"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "joaopauloxrocha", "rating": 3, "date": "2026-01-12", "title": null, "content": "Pamphlet from the Brazilian left that dominates state-funded cinema. The film is sold as a neo-noir thriller with Wagner Moura on the run from a mysterious past in Recife, but in reality it's a selective ode to the \"victim\" of the dictatorship: the pure, always-right, heroic leftist intellectual.\n\nWagner Moura acts well (he always does), the cinematography lovingly captures 1970s Recife, there's decent pacing in parts and cool references (like Tubar\u00e3o, the hairy leg). But the script is so manichean and one-sided that it becomes cheap propaganda. It only shows the side that suits today's PT narrative: \"we were the pure oppressed good guys, the coup came from eternal evil.\" It deliberately ignores that corruption and authoritarianism don't have just one side - and that plenty of people on the left back then had their own skeletons."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "db0002f7-72da-4668-bb30-eeed30ec1e9a", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.261859", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "5581393099133977d35867a3d3cf0a37d1a4c3c0aa1cae74f24f8c993b73d98b"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "fryzeegunner-83624", "rating": 5, "date": "2026-01-24", "title": null, "content": "Not the film I expected especially after the Oscar nominations. Went to the theatre today buzzing, what I walked into though was rough pacing, mid soundtrack and story lacking. 5 at best. I just couldn't connect to it and I really tried. There are much better films to consume even in 2025 alone. Disappointed."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "d5c69bd6-e3b5-45bf-8042-394c1f976392", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.261859", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "022e9199f14b97e8b0398955e82fe64ff181bd8b5e44f7941b7999a72589cb4c"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "CamaradeThia", "rating": 3, "date": "2026-01-26", "title": null, "content": "I don't know what I'd need to know about Brazil's military dictatorship period in order to grasp the purpose of this movie, if that would be helpful at all; clearly the director believes a point is being made here based on the camera constantly lingering on portraits of the president like it's a student film (something like Leviathan, a paragon of subtlety in comparison, merely includes a portrait in the shot), but judging the movie as a movie, not a visual companion to history textbooks or a vibe-focused autobiography, I thought this was atrocious.\n\nBeing chauffeured around on this tour of a cornucopia of colorful Brazilian characters, all set in decently atmospheric locations, is entertaining enough for a while - that while, for me, lasted about 30 minutes, thereat I started to really wonder when the plot would begin in earnest. The answer is it takes the Secret Agent until almost half of its outrageous 161 minute runtime to realize it forgot to begin the story, so Wagner Moura and some other characters, introduced for that scene, sits down on a couch to explain to the audience what's going on. While editing is utilized to make this scene have a bit more life to it, that didn't prevent it from cementing the movie in my mind as one filled with almost Netflix-like exposition, which, to be entirely fair, is appropriate here since you would expect the viewer to be asleep or on their phone by that point; if you aren't however, it's simply jarring to hear, for example, someone explain their family tree to a character who knows it (on account of being part of it) in this awards darling.\n\nAnd speaking of awards, of the four Oscar nominations it definitely deserves to win best casting, you're immediately impressed by the charisma of all the various guys they've got in this thing, however since there's very little connection between and rarely any point to the endless rambling vignettes they populate, they don't contribute to how enjoyable the movie is. It's surprising the cinematography didn't get a nod - I'm not saying this because it was that great, but because they used an awful lot of lenses in ways that were meant to draw attention to that fact, and Academy voters are famous for voting for whatever's easy to notice. Wagner Moura being nominated for best acting is absolutely baffling to me, he doesn't have a wide variety of expressions in this, and if there are subtleties to his performance, he must've acted so hard they ended up being imperceptible, though based on how he visibly struggles to stay awake in some moments (which - same, buddy), I doubt that's the case. My best guess would be this is a proxy nod/award for Narcos, and I would not recommend watching the Secret Agent on that basis."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "81831ff1-b2c8-472e-99ca-a90eb134c52e", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.261859", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "1ff3e673884bbbf3541cd652ec877b50c1880d5d2a5cd5ef69fa518d2dfcc866"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "Hazu29", "rating": 4, "date": "2026-01-25", "title": null, "content": "I've been watching Brazilian entertainment since the 90s. In many cases, the acting in Brazil is superior than in Hollywood, but lately the writing is getting worse and worse.\n\nWagner Moura is a great actor, he was the best in the Tropa de Elite movies and also in the Escobar Netflix show, for example. He's also quite good in this movie The Secret Agent, but unfortunately the movie is just not that good.\n\nThe Secret Agent ends up being a 4/10 movie, longer than it needed to be, very slow pace and with an enormous amount of political and social propaganda, to the point that you'll be rolling your eyes every 15 minutes.\n\nYou know the writers messed up when you end up rooting for the bad guys. That's what happened with this movie. The good guys are obnoxious and full of themselves and the bad guys are actually more genuine and, ultimately, funnier.\n\nHopefully Brazilian entertainment can go back to the good old days of Cidade de Deus.\n\nThank you for your attention."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "ade247bc-602c-403c-aa55-7a15453f1969", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.261859", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "825a112dfdeb4ee15b76e09b3f52ad47ef42d7de4359263c611ab772903c69c4"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "LeonardoOliva69", "rating": 6, "date": "2026-03-02", "title": null, "content": "What a disappointment this film was.\n\nI really wanted to love it more than any of this year's Oscar nominees.\n\nBut the truth is, I just couldn't connect with it.\n\nFirst of all, I'm Uruguayan, and I understand the social and political complexities of the civic-military dictatorships during the 70s and 80s, so I can grasp certain things that audiences in other parts of the world might not.\n\nWhat happened with this film? I think it has many interesting and impactful points, but also many others that feel disconnected.\n\nLet's talk about the good: the cinematography is a major strength; it portrays Brazil in 1977 authentically, with all that entails. Moving on to the acting, I completely believe Wagner Moura's performance, which I think is incredible. The film is full of symbolism, some more obvious, others subtle. The most eloquent aspect is Armando's son's fears about the film \"Jaws,\" which is a clear allegory for the American specter lurking behind dictatorships-a fear that is felt but not tangible. It's a real, social fear that anything happening during that era would be masked and covered up; hence the secret agent, the state. That ending, where we see the cinema that represented the people transformed into a clinic where the blood of all Brazilians is drained, is very powerful.\n\nBut there are things I really don't like about the film. I think the editing is bad, really, I don't like it; it's disjointed. There are plot threads that you don't know where they're going, what they mean, what's happening. Armando's death is completely anticlimactic, off-screen, anonymous. Why does this happen when we saw so much death in the last half hour of the film? Another thing I don't like is the pacing. We spend over an hour trying to figure out what the movie is about and why hitmen are after him. It's implied that his wife was murdered by the Brazilian government and that he had to go into hiding because of it. Again, this is very difficult to understand if you don't know the history, and while I'm a firm believer that reading is essential, not everyone will connect with this.\n\nAnother thing that bothers me is the allegory of the hairy paw. How many of us who saw the movie know that it refers to and acts as a representation of the irrational horror and state repression that terrorized the population during the dictatorship and that was used by the press to communicate this?\n\nIn short, I feel that this movie isn't the masterpiece it's being touted as during awards season. I don't think it's better than \"Sentimental Value,\" for example. I feel that last year's \"I'm Still Here\" was more representative of the turbulent times South American countries went through during those decades.\n\nOf course, this is just my opinion, and I could be wrong..."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "24d6f947-4a92-4480-807b-c9c23dbff3e3", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.261859", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "b9d26e0dc99830746346d5e35a664a3bc522c2c0902e85cdf202cdb63ab04503"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "BeneCumb", "rating": 6, "date": "2026-02-24", "title": null, "content": "The Secret Agent, directed by Kleber Mendon\u00e7a Filho, is a visually striking but divisive political thriller set during Brazil's military dictatorship in the 1970s. The story follows Armando, a political dissident played by Wagner Moura, who returns to Recife under a false name while being hunted by killers.\n\nThe basic idea is simple, but the way the story is told is complicated and often confusing. Important information is held back, and the film expects the audience to connect the dots much later. While this approach is ambitious, it often feels overly complex and emotionally distant. I frequently felt lost and had to read about the plot afterward to fully understand several twists and character motivations.\n\nTechnically, the film is strong. The cinematography beautifully captures Recife with warm, rich colours that bring the 1970s setting to life. The opening gas station scene during Carnival is intense and engaging, and the final act is thoughtful and satisfying. However, the tension suffers because the music is used too sparingly, and much of the film feels tonally flat until the last thirty minutes.\n\nMoura gives a solid and restrained performance, though it doesn't feel truly awards-worthy. T\u00e2nia Maria stands out with a strong screen presence.\n\nOverall, The Secret Agent is well made but somewhat overhyped. It is colourful, ambitious, and occasionally moving, but its long runtime (over two and a half hours) and unclear storytelling weaken its impact.\n\n6/10 - I rated it slightly higher for its exotic setting; a similar U. S. or European film might have scored lower."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "bc38defd-46e8-46d6-95b2-9ee45a1b92e7", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.262367", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "08e849676eba744ae97564623cade3e2ffa9f956646a5854fccc24a5175d6851"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "alexandergotzp", "rating": 6, "date": "2026-02-28", "title": null, "content": "Aside from the joke in the title, there is some truth in it.\n\nThe movie offers an interesting setting. Brazil in the 70s. The dictatorship. The paranoia. The daily tension of living in a country where silence could be survival. That context alone is powerful. Latin America has enough history of repression to build a thriller without inventing anything.\n\nThe problem is not the material. It is how it is delivered.\n\nThe film is painfully slow. Even for a political thriller. It drops hints about who the characters are, what they did, how they are connected. But the hints are so subtle that following the story becomes an exercise rather than an experience. I was fully paying attention in the cinema and still felt like I was missing something. Not because it is deep, but because it seems engineered to be obscure.\n\nThroughout the film you wait for a payoff. You assume the climax will justify the restraint, the bland dialogues, the focus on ordinary daily routines. But when the climax finally arrives, yes, there are deaths, but they do not land. You were never allowed to truly connect with anyone except the main character, and even his story is never fully told.\n\nSome critics might say that is the point. That the emotional distance reflects the cold machinery of dictatorship. Maybe. But intention does not automatically create impact. If the audience leaves without feeling the weight of what happened, something is missing.\n\nThen there is the leg that comes back to life. A clear nod to magical realism, to Latin American literature. On paper, interesting. In practice, completely out of place. It feels like a different film inserted into this one. Instead of enriching the narrative, it fragments it even more.\n\nAt moments the movie feels like a series of recordings stitched together. Detached. Observational. Just like the women listening to tapes inside the story. You keep waiting for cohesion.\n\nI respect the decision to tell the story in that fragmented way. It is bold. It is controlled. It is deliberate. But it is also distant. There is too much hype around the craftsmanship and not enough emotional payoff.\n\nKudos to Wagner Moura. His presence anchors the film.\n\nBut for me, not kudos to the director."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "9b615069-7e02-4b30-bacc-500b49d25ff9", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.262367", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "fca83205d049ad8aeb9409821ac232a09a8f08f4893bfe8afbe3e935e8031cc5"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "Freethinker_Atheist", "rating": 1, "date": "2026-01-30", "title": null, "content": "I'm Brazilian, politically on the left and a fan of Wagner Moura, but this movie is not good. Normally, I'm extremely tolerant when it comes to movies. I even like to watch bad movies, such as \"Manos: The Hands of Fate\", because they are so bad that they are good. \"O Agente Secreto\", however, is just plain bad. It's so bad that I even left the cinema in the middle of the film (something I almost never do). This movie is not only slow and waaaaay overlong, it also doesn't know what kind of movie it wants to be. The story is all over the place, with loads of blablabla, characters and situations that cutting them out would change nothing in the story, which lacks suspense anyway. Movies like this win prizes not because they are well-made, but because they are \"exotic\" (Europeans love that) and because of their political message. I wasted my time, but at least I didn't waste my money. It was a free ticket.\n\nPS: The movie's title is total nonsense."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "ba9bf2bd-17b5-49dd-a2df-91fa40015f95", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.262367", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "93f49d36fc180fc07184aff7bdc5a75d3ef05a369886dda3c571352813c5152a"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "HighlanderABC", "rating": 5, "date": "2026-01-31", "title": null, "content": "Only decided to watch the movie because the main actor used to have a pretty good role in the TV series Narcos not that long ago. But the storyline and directing of this movie is very disappointing. I watched the first 30 minutes and just couldn't continue anymore because I'm confused on what the story is about and where the movie is going. Lots of random pieces without any cohesiveness or attraction especially to someone who's not familiar with that era or that area of the world. Pretty boring to say the least."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "009ac891-ebc0-442b-9d48-c87eef46b132", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.262367", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "e759f651ca182eb2da3a3b659bbc7e729332f7f505d391f376507d150cf90f1d"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "jboothmillard", "rating": 6, "date": "2026-02-27", "title": null, "content": "It is fair to say that I went to see this Brazilian film purely because it received various accolades during Awards Season, but many foreign language films have gained my admiration, and I was hoping this would be another one, directed by Kleber Mendon\u00e7a Filho (Bacurau). Basically, in 1977, during the political turmoil of the Brazilian military dictatorship, former professor and widower Armando Solim\u00f5es (Golden Globe winning, and Oscar nominated Wagner Moura) travels to Recife, Pernambuco, during the carnival holiday, where his young son Fernando (Enzo Nunes) has been living with his in-laws since his wife, F\u00e1tima Nascimento (Alice Carvalho), passed away. He arrives at a refuge operated by former far-left communist Dona Sebastiana (T\u00e2nia Maria), where he adopts the name Marcelo and befriends other political protestors, including Claudia (Hermila Guedes), Haroldo (Jo\u00e3o Vitor Silva) and Angolan Civil War refugees, Thereza Vit\u00f3ria (Isab\u00e9l Zuaa) and Antonio (Lic\u00ednio Janu\u00e1rio). Meanwhile, corrupt Civil Police chief Euclides Cavalcanti (Rob\u00e9rio Di\u00f3genes) and his sons Sergio (Igor de Ara\u00fajo) and Arlindo (Italo Martins) are called in to investigate a severed human leg that has been found inside the stomach of a tiger shark. Armando is placed in a job by his protestor network at the city's identity card office under the alias of Marcelo, where he has a chance encounter with Euclides, who offers him his friendship and protection. Armando is visibly irritated by Euclides's arrogant behaviour, which includes harassing Jewish Holocaust survivor Hans (Udo Kier, in his last posthumous role), who is mistakenly assumed to be a Nazi fugitive. Armando's job allows him to search for files on his late mother, whom he has some memories of. Meanwhile, in S\u00e3o Paulo, hitmen Bobbi (Gabriel Leone) and Augusto (Roney Villela) are hired by former Eletrobras executive director Henrique Ghirotti (Luciano Chirolli) to kill Armando, whom he has a political and personal vendetta against. Armando meets political resistance movement leader Elza (Maria Fernanda C\u00e2ndido) at the Cinema S\u00e3o Luiz, where his father-in-law Sr. Alexandre (Carlos Francisco) works as a projectionist. Recording a testimony about Ghirotti's corrupt activities, Armando recounts a dinner he went to with F\u00e1tima that ended in a physical argument with Ghirotti and his son, following remarks on the couple's lower socioeconomic class and supposed communist sympathies. Elza informs Armando that a contract killing has been ordered and instructs him to flee the country. Sergio and Arlindo dump the human leg in the Capibaribe River, where it suddenly comes to life and attacks gay men cruising in a public park at night. The story of the leg attacking, presumably a newspaper cover-up for the political corruption and violence during the carnival week, creates a public frenzy. Augusto and Bobbi hire penniless gunman Vilmar (Kaiony Ven\u00e2ncio) to find Armando. Anticipating a departure, Armando bids farewell to Dona Sebastiana and the other refugees. The following day, Armando's cover is blown after Bobbi closely monitors Sr. Alexandre. Vilmar identifies Armando but fails to kill him, shooting Arlindo and a fellow police officer. Bobbi, watching from a distance, chases a bleeding Vilmar through Recife's city centre and eventually finds and kills Vilmar in a barbershop. In the present day, history student Flavia (Laura Luf\u00e9si) is researching Elza and the resistance network through audio recordings and newspaper archives. She learns that Armando was murdered and framed as a corrupt professor. Travelling to Recife, Flavia meets with Fernando, who has become a middle-aged doctor. He agrees to be interviewed in the hospital where he works after Flavia donates blood. The pair discuss Armando's political past and subsequent assassination, and the identity of Armando's mother, \"India\". Fernando states he has no memory whatsoever of his father, but fondly recalls watching Jaws with his grandfather. The cinema he went to see the movie has since become the hospital where he works. Also starring Enzo Nunes as young Fernando Solim\u00f5es, Isadora Ruppert as Daniela, and Aline Marta Maia as Lenira Nascimento. The scenes and moments that stand out are the opening scenes at the petrol station with the dead body, the boy obsessed with Jaws including drawing his own posters, the severed leg reanimating and kicking people to death, the chase through ending in the barbershop, and obviously the present day ending with the former cinema reveal, but I must admit I struggled to understand everything going on. The main plot involves a mysterious bloke wanting to connect with his son while there is a complex story dealing with corruption, chaos, and carnival; it has eye-catching period detail, memorably engaging and bizarre parts (a two-faced cat and the leg kicking people are random and perhaps too weird), and it is unclassifiable, but I can see why it has gained attention, it is an unusual but equally fascinating neo-noir historical political thriller. It is nominated the Oscars for Best International Feature Film, Best Picture, and Best Casting, it was nominated the BAFTAs for Best Film Not in the English Language, and Best Original Screenplay, and it won the Golden Globe for Best Motion Picture - Non-English Language, and it was nominated for Best Motion Picture - Drama. Good!"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "1354983e-db94-49ca-befe-712e1dea828e", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.262367", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "b358003f2343218f5bba48a47b534647b64ac4371a0a5eccabc731678bcf6dcf"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "andreadjokickv", "rating": 3, "date": "2026-01-29", "title": null, "content": "If I could give this movie one star, I would (I can, but out of respect for Moura, I won't).\n\nI really wanted to like this film. I was extremely hyped before watching it, and I watched it attentively, yet it kept disappointing me minute after minute. The movie's potentially amazing story failed to deliver its quality for several reasons.\n\nFirst, the pacing is highly problematic. During the first half of the film, you're barely given any hints about what the story is actually about, and you're introduced to a variety of characters who add nothing to the plot or the main character's development. Then the film finally gets to the core of what happened, but even there you're given only incoherent fragments, with some parts making no sense whatsoever.\n\nAnd the finale completely ruined it for me. After so much back-and-forth, the main character's ending is one of the most underwhelming I've ever seen. I honestly felt betrayed and angry.\n\nThe film is also far too long. It should have been at least an hour shorter and features about five characters more than necessary.\n\nAll in all, one of the biggest disappointments of last/this year."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "35b08033-6855-4f9d-aa8d-034ce1d377a0", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.262367", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "86b10822417b55ab5243a284c425478b7eef163481b6f4170892215fbc055b9f"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "eddie_baggins", "rating": 6, "date": "2026-02-17", "title": null, "content": "I couldn't shake the feeling with The Secret Agent, Kleber Mendon\u00e7a Filho's Brazilian set epic that takes us back to the political upheaval in the country in the late 1970's, that what I was witnessing was a decent film that has been made out to be a great one, one that has managed to receive amongst many other plaudits 4 Oscar nominations that should have arguably been taken up by other films of the 2025 class.\n\nClocking in at a bum-numbing two hours and 40 minutes, Agent see's Filho deliver an on paper simplistic set up in a complicated way, creating an at times downright messy and convoluted plot line that is brilliantly filmed and staged but devoid of much heart and soul as Wagner Moura's critical darling performance as Armando Solim\u00f5es walks us through this pretty mess.\n\nOpening with a fantastic segment at a rural gas station during Brazil's Carnival holiday period in a time in the country where corruption, civil unrest and political upheaval was running rife through the nation, Agent kicks off with a bang but at multiple time falls of the cliff with unnecessary scenes and an unwarranted storytelling delivery that makes Agent at times hard to really connect with and follow, despite its repeated attempts to show you how smart it all is.\n\nReceiving Oscar nominations in categories that includes coveted spots for Best Feature, Best Casting and Best Actor, it's particularly sad that Agent's prominence in these spaces took spots from the likes of Jesse Plemons or Joel Edgerton in the acting space or Train Dreams in the Best Casting category and while Moura certainly gives it his all, his much lauded performance here doesn't exactly demand we stand to attention.\n\nHaving long been a prominent player in the likes of hit shows such as Narcos or Dope Thief and films such as Civil War and Elite Squad, Moura is as good as his ever been but it doesn't feel like a performance or role that will be talked about in the years yet to come, with the talented performer overshadowed here by the likes of T\u00e2nia Maria as Dona Sebastiana, a character you almost wish would become the central focus of the film.\n\nEverything is all very unconventional here in a lot of ways, the way in which the film is edited, its much talked about final act and zany score from composers Tomaz Alves Souza Mateus Alves all working to create the odd vibe Filho was going for but you can't help but escape the feeling that Agent was one of those films, one of a few that come around every year, where critics didn't want to speak up against it and general public didn't want to buck the trend and suggest it just wasn't as good as many have made it out to be.\n\nFinal Say -\n\nThe Secret Agent is a perfectly decent film but one that outstays its welcome on more than one occasion and benefits little from its odd storytelling approach. Pretty to look at and unquestionably unique, when you consider the other films contending for this year's Best Picture Oscar, this one stands out for all the wrong reasons.\n\n3 filing cabinets out of 5."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "2f14db7e-4872-492d-bd30-576dc0c7be83", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.262367", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "1eb3b8ab54fc4c6a4ad60a43d0c10591f3106c5419541c11092a6002b3c82924"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "tm-sheehan", "rating": 5, "date": "2026-01-30", "title": null, "content": "My Review- The Secret Agent In Cinemas now My Rating 5/10\n\nIt always puzzles me as to why foreign language movies are eligible for a double dip at the Oscar's to possibly win Best Movie in a Foreign Language as well as Best Movie of the year? So I did some research and the short answer was that the Academy's top prize has never had a language restriction. If a film meets the general eligibility it can compete for Best Picture regardless of language or country of origin.\n\nFor decades, international films were effectively siloed or ignored so the Academy decided that allowing TV crossover of categories prevented the ghettoisation of non-English cinema signalling that world cinema is not \"separate but equal\" plus acknowledging that a masterpiece doesn't become \"lesser\" because it has subtitles.\n\nMy question to the Academy is by including two foreign language movies as they have this year in the Best Film as well as Best foreign language creates a disadvantage to two of the best English language movies eg -Nuremberg or The Choral .\n\nOh well , let's talk about The Secret Agent the highly praised Brazilian movie that's nominated for 4 Oscars this year including Best Picture, Best International Feature Movie , Best Actor for its star Wagner Mourer and Best Casting.\n\nIf I was voting I wouldn't vote for The Secret Agent in any of those categories because I found it to long at 161 minutes, to disjointed and while realising the script may be better than the subtitles suggest not very interesting.\n\nSet in 1977 Brazil Wagner Mourer is a good choice for the role of Marcelo a technology expert who becomes a fugitive on the run.\n\nHoping to reunite with his son, he travels to Recife during Carnival but soon realizes that the city is not the safe haven he was expecting.\n\nIt may well have got lost in translation however it's completion from Norway Sentimental Value for me is a far superior movie in every way because I could identify with every character and every scene interested me .\n\nIf anyone can explain the bizarre scene in this movie of a severed leg that was found in a sharks belly suddenly coming to life while kicking gay men in a park I'd appreciate finding an answer?\n\nThe continual toing and froing back and forth made the timeline of the movie confusing for me and the conclusion after so many unnecessary scenes seemed rushed and unexplained.\n\nI've seen some wonderful Brazilian movies like the 1998 Central Station and the stunning I'm Still Here 2025 but I can't add The Secret Agent to my list."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "161907ef-9bbc-4245-9a13-83d5486943a6", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.262367", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "8c27303cd9c739476418ea3cdf2d6bd35354c7f7dba6ca516cdf9d6467983f31"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "Gl0bal_Warning", "rating": 6, "date": "2026-01-28", "title": null, "content": "Impressive acting for the protagonist in his first film, apparently, beautiful colors, great locations, great production, and reconstruction of the 70's vibes, every single scene was made expertly.\n\nAfter a beautiful introduction to his life, what's up with this story? There are too many holes and mistakes; why lose half of the movie's time with the recording of the tape? I lost all connection with the movie at the halfway mark. I was almost shocked by how the movie started to go downhill. Such a waste of acting skills ruined by a story that still makes no sense to me. Was this taken from a book? If so, why did nobody think that was a boring story, and do something more original, even if the story is true, is a big pile of nothing?\n\nSo much hard work for something that could be made for an episode of some thriller Series done in 25 minutes. People giving 10/10 are delusional. If this had a great story could have been a Brazilian masterpiece of cinematography. Let's hope the next film the director gets some compelling story to work with."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "5abe4d66-1ed8-4737-8f82-fb27ec74f844", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.262367", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "8d58d72fe9741b87dbf51396e0ed1242fffb6eb53f842662684771dd145592b5"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "martimusross", "rating": 2, "date": "2026-02-14", "title": null, "content": "The Secret Agent\n\nThe title presupposes a thriller with espionage, a strong story, well written characters and some thrilling action, instead we got this glacial tripe!\n\nI am not suggesting that it was all bad, there were some redeeming factors for this movie. Firstly the styling and cinematography was really top quality. We really felt we were in 1977, what with the Volkswagen beetles the dodgy haircuts and cheese cloth shirts but quite frankly that was about it.\n\nThere was just not sufficient here to sustain a movie of two hours and 41 minutes, the story was tissue thin. It amounted to a man that had upset his boss and gone into hiding over research money that was somehow being stolen. It seemed to me the movie displayed endemic corruption in Brazil in the 1970s linked to organised crime that just made any person that stood in their way disappear.\n\nThe movie was glacially slow as we just saw characters going about their daily lives. It had very much a documentary feel about it with no narrative impetus and no character development.\n\nAgain, I cannot see why this movie has been nominated in the Oscars, we do not nominate movies because they are worthy. They are nominated because of excellence, any other elevation of a movie brings the Oscars into disrepute. However, it is often the case that it is just sufficient to nominate and not to award to make the point.\n\nI'm going to give this a 2 outta 10 it really was a two hour and 41 minute waste of my life."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "38fd5225-783f-481b-9f32-7862135581c1", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:25.262367", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "4eeed2272a45f2a1ab39ce829cb6ab32cf3fd2bbaed41d323c0f0f46b451e9df"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27847051", "author": "carmelolia", "rating": 8, "date": "2026-03-06", "title": null, "content": "This is one of those films that leaves you scratching your head a little after its 2 hours and 41 minutes runtime. Directed by Brazilian director, Kleber Mendonca Filho, and starring Wagner Moura, the film takes us back to 1970s Brazil during \"a time of great mischief.\" What stood out to me most wasn't the political aspect, but the Brazilian atmosphere and the people. Beneath the tension and paranoia, the film quietly celebrates the Brazilian family spirit, friends and relatives gathering, sharing food, joking, and looking out for one another even in a country plagued by corruption, surveillance, and abuse of power. It's a small but touching reminder that ordinary warmth can survive even in oppressive times, and it reminds me very much of my country, Malta, as well.\n\nOne of the film's more interesting ideas is its obsession with facades. Almost everyone seems to be hiding something, living a double life of sorts, and the strange image of the two-headed cat works as a neat little symbol for that theme. Two faces, two stories, two truths. In a way, the title starts to feel less literal: the \"secret agent\" could be anyone, because everyone is protecting some private version of themselves. Mendonca Filho also throws in some odd, almost folkloric moments that blur the line between reality and myth, an unusual stylistic choice that gives the film a distinctive flavour, even if I personally do not think it is incorporated well into the story.\n\nThat said, the film isn't flawless. Some stretches are undeniably slow, occasionally drifting into monotony, and the modern day ending feels a bit anti-climactic after spending so much time immersed in the wonderfully recreated 1970s setting. Still, there's a lot to admire here: the careful period detail, the thoughtful themes, and Moura's performance. It may not be a film I loved every minute of, but it's certainly one I respected, and in today's cinema landscape, that already counts for quite a lot."}}
